[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] This is a property of a system—whether a program, computer, or a network—where there is a separate execution point or "thread of control" for each process.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] A *concurrent system* is one where a computation can advance without waiting for all other computations to complete.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computing is a form of modular programming.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] In its paradigm an overall computation is factored into subcomputations that may be executed concurrently.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Pioneers in the field of concurrent computing include Edsger Dijkstra, Per Brinch Hansen, and C.A.R.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] The concept of concurrent computing is frequently confused with the related but distinct concept of parallel computing, although both can be described as "multiple processes executing *during the same period of time*".
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] By contrast, concurrent computing consists of process *lifetimes* overlapping, but execution does not happen at the same instant.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] The goal here is to model processes that happen concurrently, like multiple clients accessing a server at the same time.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Structuring software systems as composed of multiple concurrent, communicating parts can be useful for tackling complexity, regardless of whether the parts can be executed in parallel.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] In this way, multiple processes are part-way through execution at a single instant, but only one process is being executed at that instant.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computations *may* be executed in parallel, for example, by assigning each process to a separate processor or processor core, or distributing a computation across a network.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] The exact timing of when tasks in a concurrent system are executed depends on the scheduling, and tasks need not always be executed concurrently.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] The word "sequential" is used as an antonym for both "concurrent" and "parallel"; when these are explicitly distinguished, *concurrent/sequential* and *parallel/serial* are used as opposing pairs.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] A schedule in which tasks execute one at a time (serially, no parallelism), without interleaving (sequentially, no concurrency: no task begins until the prior task ends) is called a *serial schedule*.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] A set of tasks that can be scheduled serially is *serializable*, which simplifies concurrency control.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] The main challenge in designing concurrent programs is concurrency control: ensuring the correct sequencing of the interactions or communications between different computational executions, and coordinating access to resources that are shared among executions.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Potential problems include race conditions, deadlocks, and resource starvation.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Suppose `balance = 500`, and two concurrent *threads* make the calls `withdraw(300)` and `withdraw(350)`.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] If line 3 in both operations executes before line 5 both operations will find that `balance >= withdrawal` evaluates to `true`, and execution will proceed to subtracting the withdrawal amount.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] However, since both processes perform their withdrawals, the total amount withdrawn will end up being more than the original balance.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] These sorts of problems with shared resources benefit from the use of concurrency control, or non-blocking algorithms.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Introduced in 1962, Petri nets were an early attempt to codify the rules of concurrent execution.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Dataflow theory later built upon these, and Dataflow architectures were created to physically implement the ideas of dataflow theory.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Beginning in the late 1970s, process calculi such as Calculus of Communicating Systems (CCS) and Communicating Sequential Processes (CSP) were developed to permit algebraic reasoning about systems composed of interacting components.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] The π-calculus added the capability for reasoning about dynamic topologies.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Input/output automata were introduced in 1987.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Logics such as Lamport's TLA+, and mathematical models such as traces and Actor event diagrams, have also been developed to describe the behavior of concurrent systems.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Software transactional memory borrows from database theory the concept of atomic transactions and applies them to memory accesses.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Concurrent programming languages and multiprocessor programs must have a consistency model (also known as a memory model).
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] The consistency model defines rules for how operations on computer memory occur and how results are produced.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] One of the first consistency models was Leslie Lamport's sequential consistency model.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Sequential consistency is the property of a program that its execution produces the same results as a sequential program.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Specifically, a program is sequentially consistent if "the results of any execution is the same as if the operations of all the processors were executed in some sequential order, and the operations of each individual processor appear in this sequence in the order specified by its program".
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] A number of different methods can be used to implement concurrent programs, such as implementing each computational execution as an operating system process, or implementing the computational processes as a set of threads within a single operating system process.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] In some concurrent computing systems, communication between the concurrent components is hidden from the programmer (e.g., by using futures), while in others it must be handled explicitly.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] The exchange of messages may be carried out asynchronously, or may use a synchronous "rendezvous" style in which the sender blocks until the message is received.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Asynchronous message passing may be reliable or unreliable (sometimes referred to as "send and pray").
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Message-passing concurrency tends to be far easier to reason about than shared-memory concurrency, and is typically considered a more robust form of concurrent programming.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Shared memory and message passing concurrency have different performance characteristics.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Typically (although not always), the per-process memory overhead and task switching overhead is lower in a message passing system, but the overhead of message passing is greater than for a procedure call.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] These differences are often overwhelmed by other performance factors.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computing developed out of earlier work on railroads and telegraphy, from the 19th and early 20th century, and some terms date to this period, such as semaphores.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] These arose to address the question of how to handle multiple trains on the same railroad system (avoiding collisions and maximizing efficiency) and how to handle multiple transmissions over a given set of wires (improving efficiency), such as via time-division multiplexing (1870s).
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] The academic study of concurrent algorithms started in the 1960s, with Dijkstra (1965) credited with being the first paper in this field, identifying and solving mutual exclusion.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Concurrency is pervasive in computing, occurring from low-level hardware on a single chip to worldwide networks.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] At the network level, networked systems are generally concurrent by their nature, as they consist of separate devices.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Concurrent programming languages are programming languages that use language constructs for concurrency.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] These constructs may involve multi-threading, support for distributed computing, message passing, shared resources (including shared memory) or futures and promises.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Such languages are sometimes described as *concurrency-oriented languages* or *concurrency-oriented programming languages* (COPL).
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Today, the most commonly used programming languages that have specific constructs for concurrency are Java and C#.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Both of these languages fundamentally use a shared-memory concurrency model, with locking provided by monitors (although message-passing models can and have been implemented on top of the underlying shared-memory model).
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Of the languages that use a message-passing concurrency model, Erlang was probably the most widely used in industry as of 2010.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Many concurrent programming languages have been developed more as research languages (e.g., Pict) rather than as languages for production use.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] However, languages such as Erlang, Limbo, and occam have seen industrial use at various times in the last 20 years.
[src:trio-async/concurrent-computing] Many other languages provide support for concurrency in the form of libraries, at levels roughly comparable with the above list.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] They have been described as "functions whose execution you can pause".
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Melvin Conway coined the term *coroutine* in 1958 when he applied it to the construction of an assembly program.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] The first published explanation of the coroutine appeared later, in 1963.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] There is no single precise definition of coroutine.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] 2. the execution of a coroutine is suspended as control leaves it, only to carry on where it left off when control re-enters the coroutine at some later stage.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] 3. whether a coroutine is able to suspend its execution from within nested function calls.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Such a coroutine is a *stackful coroutine*.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] One to the contrary is called *stackless coroutines*, where unless marked as coroutine, a regular function can't use the keyword `yield`.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] The paper "Revisiting Coroutines" published in 2009 proposed the term *full coroutine* to denote one that supports first-class coroutine and is stackful.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Full Coroutines deserve their own name in that they have the same expressive power as one-shot continuations and delimited continuations.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Full coroutines are either symmetric or asymmetric.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Importantly, whether a coroutine is symmetric or asymmetric has no bearing on how expressive it can be, though full coroutines are more expressive than non-full coroutines.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] While their expressive power is the same, asymmetrical coroutines more closely resemble routine based control structures in the sense that control is always passed back to the invoker, which programmers may find more familiar.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Subroutines are special cases of coroutines.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] When subroutines are invoked, execution begins at the start, and once a subroutine exits, it is finished; an instance of a subroutine only returns once, and does not hold state between invocations.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] By contrast, coroutines can exit by calling other coroutines, which may later return to the point where they were invoked in the original coroutine; from the coroutine's point of view, it is not exiting but calling another coroutine.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Thus, a coroutine instance holds state, and varies between invocations; there can be multiple instances of a given coroutine at once.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] The difference between calling another coroutine by means of "yielding" to it and simply calling another routine (which then, also, would return to the original point), is that the relationship between two coroutines which yield to each other is not that of caller-callee, but instead symmetric.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Any subroutine can be translated to a coroutine which does not call *yield*.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Here is a simple example of how coroutines can be useful.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Suppose you have a consumer-producer relationship where one routine creates items and adds them to a queue and another removes items from the queue and uses them.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] For reasons of efficiency, you want to add and remove several items at once.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] The queue is then completely filled or emptied before yielding control to the other coroutine using the *yield* command.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] The further coroutines calls are starting right after the *yield*, in the outer coroutine loop.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Although this example is often used as an introduction to multithreading, two threads are not needed for this: the *yield* statement can be implemented by a jump directly from one routine into the other.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] However, coroutines are cooperatively multitasked, whereas threads are typically preemptively multitasked.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Coroutines provide concurrency, because they allow tasks to be performed out of order or in a changeable order, without changing the overall outcome, but they do not provide parallelism, because they do not execute multiple tasks simultaneously.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] It is possible to implement coroutines using preemptively-scheduled threads, in a way that will be transparent to the calling code, but some of the advantages (particularly the suitability for hard-realtime operation and relative cheapness of switching between them) will be lost.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Generators, also known as semicoroutines, are a subset of coroutines.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] That is, since generators are primarily used to simplify the writing of iterators, the `yield` statement in a generator does not specify a coroutine to jump to, but rather passes a value back to a parent routine.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] A number of implementations of coroutines for languages with generator support but no native coroutines (e.g.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Python before 2.5) use this or a similar model.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Using coroutines for state machines or concurrency is similar to using mutual recursion with tail calls, as in both cases the control changes to a different one of a set of routines.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] However, coroutines are more flexible and generally more efficient.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Further, each mutually recursive call of a subroutine requires a new stack frame (unless tail call elimination is implemented), while passing control between coroutines uses the existing contexts and can be implemented simply by a jump.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Coroutines originated as an assembly language method, but are supported in some high-level programming languages.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Java does not have native or library support for coroutines, but it can call Kotlin coroutines `kotlinx.coroutines` (though this is not ideal and would require a Java wrapper over Kotlin).
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Since continuations can be used to implement coroutines, programming languages that support them can also quite easily support coroutines.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] As of 2003, many of the most popular programming languages, including C and its derivatives, do not have built-in support for coroutines within the language or their standard libraries.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] This is, in large part, due to the limitations of stack-based subroutine implementation.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] An exception is the C++ library Boost.Context, part of Boost, which supports context swapping on ARM, MIPS, PowerPC, SPARC and x86 on POSIX, Mac OS X and Windows.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Coroutines can be built upon Boost.Context.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Conditionals within the code result in the execution of different code paths on successive calls, based on the values of the state variables.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Another typical response is to implement an explicit state machine in the form of a large and complex switch statement or via a goto statement, particularly a computed goto.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Such implementations are considered difficult to understand and maintain, and a motivation for coroutine support.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Threads, and to a lesser extent fibers, are an alternative to coroutines in mainstream programming environments today.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Threads provide facilities for managing the real-time cooperative interaction of *simultaneously* executing pieces of code.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Threads are widely available in environments that support C (and are supported natively in many other modern languages), are familiar to many programmers, and are usually well-implemented, well-documented and well-supported.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] However, as they solve a large and difficult problem they include many powerful and complex facilities and have a correspondingly difficult learning curve.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] As such, when a coroutine is all that is needed, using a thread can be overkill.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] One important difference between threads and coroutines is that threads are typically preemptively scheduled while coroutines are not.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Because threads can be rescheduled at any instant and can execute concurrently, programs using threads must be careful about locking.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] In contrast, because coroutines can only be rescheduled at specific points in the program and do not execute concurrently, programs using coroutines can often avoid locking entirely.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] This property is also cited as a benefit of event-driven or asynchronous programming.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Since fibers are cooperatively scheduled, they provide an ideal base for implementing coroutines above.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] However, system support for fibers is often lacking compared to that for threads.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] In order to implement general-purpose coroutines, a second call stack must be obtained, which is a feature not directly supported by the C language.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] A reliable (albeit platform-specific) way to achieve this is to use a small amount of inline assembly to explicitly manipulate the stack pointer during initial creation of the coroutine.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] This is the approach recommended by Tom Duff in a discussion on its relative merits vs. the method used by Protothreads.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] On platforms which provide the POSIX sigaltstack system call, a second call stack can be obtained by calling a springboard function from within a signal handler to achieve the same goal in portable C, at the cost of some extra complexity.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] C libraries complying to POSIX or the Single Unix Specification (SUSv3) provided such routines as getcontext, setcontext, makecontext and swapcontext, but these functions were declared obsolete in POSIX 1.2008.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Once a second call stack has been obtained with one of the methods listed above, the setjmp and longjmp functions in the standard C library can then be used to implement the switches between coroutines.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] These functions save and restore, respectively, the stack pointer, program counter, callee-saved registers, and any other internal state as required by the ABI, such that returning to a coroutine after having yielded restores all the state that would be restored upon returning from a function call.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Minimalist implementations, which do not piggyback off the setjmp and longjmp functions, may achieve the same result via a small block of inline assembly which swaps merely the stack pointer and program counter, and clobbers all other registers.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] This can be significantly faster, as setjmp and longjmp must conservatively store all registers which may be in use according to the ABI, whereas the clobber method allows the compiler to store (by spilling to the stack) only what it knows is actually in use.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Due to the lack of direct language support, many authors have written their own libraries for coroutines which hide the above details.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Russ Cox's libtask library is a good example of this genre.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] It uses the context functions if they are provided by the native C library; otherwise it provides its own implementations for ARM, PowerPC, Sparc, and x86.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Other notable implementations include libpcl, coro, lthread, libCoroutine, libconcurrency, libcoro, ribs2, libdill., libaco, and libco.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] In addition to the general approach above, several attempts have been made to approximate coroutines in C with combinations of subroutines and macros.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Simon Tatham's contribution, based on Duff's device, is a notable example of the genre, and is the basis for Protothreads and similar implementations.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] C++20 introduced standardized coroutines as stackless functions that can be suspended in the middle of execution and resumed at a later point.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] The suspended state of a coroutine is stored on the heap.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Implementation of this standard is ongoing, with the G++ and MSVC compilers currently fully supporting standard coroutines in recent versions.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] A generator class for synchronous and lazy-evaluated ranges, `std::generator`, was added in C++23.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] A proper task class, `std::execution::task`, was introduced in C++26.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] It is invoked using `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] This is an example of C++20 coroutines with the C++26 `std::execution::task` class.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] C# 2.0 added semi-coroutine (generator) functionality through the iterator pattern and `yield` keyword.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Cloroutine is a third-party library providing support for stackless coroutines in Clojure.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] It's implemented as a macro, statically splitting an arbitrary code block on arbitrary var calls and emitting the coroutine as a stateful function.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] D implements coroutines as its standard library class `core.thread.Fiber` for a fiber.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] A generator (`std.concurrency.Generator`) makes it trivial to expose a fiber function as an input range (`std.range.interfaces.InputRange`), making any fiber compatible with existing range algorithms.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Go has a built-in concept of "goroutines", a type of green thread which are lightweight, independent processes managed by the Go runtime.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] A new goroutine can be started using the "go" keyword.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Each goroutine has a variable-size stack which can be expanded as needed.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Goroutines generally communicate using Go's built-in channels.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] However, goroutines are not coroutines (for instance, local data does not persist between successive calls).
[src:trio-async/coroutine] There are several implementations for coroutines in Java.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Despite the constraints imposed by Java's abstractions, the JVM does not preclude the possibility.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] There are four general methods used, but two break bytecode portability among standards-compliant JVMs.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Since ECMAScript 2015, JavaScript has support for generators, which are a special case of coroutines.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Kotlin implements coroutines as part of a first-party library.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Lua has supported first-class stackful asymmetric coroutines since version 5.0 (2003), in the standard library *coroutine*.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Modula-2 as defined by Wirth implements coroutines as part of the standard SYSTEM library.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] The procedure NEWPROCESS() fills in a context given a code block and space for a stack as parameters, and the procedure TRANSFER() transfers control to a coroutine given the coroutine's context as its parameter.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] The Mono Common Language Runtime has support for continuations, from which coroutines can be built.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] During the development of the .NET Framework 2.0, Microsoft extended the design of the Common Language Runtime (CLR) hosting APIs to handle fiber-based scheduling with an eye towards its use in fiber-mode for SQL server.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Before release, support for the task switching hook `ICLRTask::SwitchOut` was removed due to time constraints.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Consequently, the use of the fiber API to switch tasks is currently not a viable option in the .NET Framework.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] OCaml supports coroutines through its `Thread` module.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] These coroutines provide concurrency without parallelism, and are scheduled preemptively on a single operating system thread.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Since OCaml 5.0, green threads are also available; provided by different modules.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Coroutines are natively implemented in all Raku backends.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Python has support for coroutines using the `asyncio.create_task()` function.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Racket provides native continuations, with a trivial implementation of coroutines provided in the official package catalog.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Since Scheme provides full support for continuations, implementing coroutines is nearly trivial, requiring only that a queue of continuations be maintained.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Since, in most Smalltalk environments, the execution stack is a first-class citizen, coroutines can be implemented without additional library or VM support.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Since version 8.6, Tcl supports coroutines in the core language.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Vala implements native support for coroutines.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] They are designed to be used with a GTK Main Loop, but can be used alone if care is taken to ensure that the end callback will never have to be called before doing, at least, one yield.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Machine-dependent assembly languages often provide direct methods for coroutine execution.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] On VAXen (in VAX MACRO) the comparable instruction is "JSB @(SP)+".
[src:trio-async/coroutine] Even on a Motorola 6809 there is the instruction "JSR [,S++]"; note the "++", as 2 bytes (of address) are popped from the stack.
[src:trio-async/coroutine] This instruction is much used in the (standard) 'monitor' Assist 09.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] In concurrent computing, **deadlock** is any situation in which no member of some group of entities can proceed because each waits for another member, including itself, to take action, such as sending a message or, more commonly, releasing a lock.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] Deadlocks are a common problem in multiprocessing systems, parallel computing, and distributed systems, because in these contexts systems often use software or hardware locks to arbitrate shared resources and implement process synchronization.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] In an operating system, a deadlock occurs when a process or thread enters a waiting state because a requested system resource is held by another waiting process, which in turn is waiting for another resource held by another waiting process.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] If a process remains indefinitely unable to change its state because resources requested by it are being used by another process that itself is waiting, then the system is said to be in a deadlock.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] In a communications system, deadlocks occur mainly due to loss or corruption of signals rather than contention for resources.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] *Hold and wait* or *resource holding:* a process is currently holding at least one resource and requesting additional resources which are being held by other processes.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] *No preemption:* a resource can be released only voluntarily by the process holding it.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] *Circular wait:* each process must be waiting for a resource which is being held by another process, which in turn is waiting for the first process to release the resource.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] In general, there is a set of waiting processes, *P* = {*P*1, *P*2, ..., *P**N*}, such that *P*1 is waiting for a resource held by *P*2, *P*2 is waiting for a resource held by *P*3 and so on until *P**N* is waiting for a resource held by *P*1.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] These four conditions are known as the *Coffman conditions* from their first description in a 1971 article by Edward G.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] While these conditions are sufficient to produce a deadlock on single-instance resource systems, they only indicate the possibility of deadlock on systems having multiple instances of resources.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] Most current operating systems cannot prevent deadlocks.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] When a deadlock occurs, different operating systems respond to them in different non-standard manners.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] Most approaches work by preventing one of the four *Coffman conditions* from occurring, especially the fourth one.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] In this approach, it is assumed that a deadlock will never occur.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] This is also an application of the Ostrich algorithm.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] This approach was initially used by MINIX and UNIX.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] This is used when the time intervals between occurrences of deadlocks are large and the data loss incurred each time is tolerable.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] Ignoring deadlocks can be safely done if deadlocks are formally proven to never occur.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] Under the deadlock detection, deadlocks are allowed to occur.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] Then the state of the system is examined to detect that a deadlock has occurred and subsequently it is corrected.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] An algorithm is employed that tracks resource allocation and process states, it rolls back and restarts one or more of the processes in order to remove the detected deadlock.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] Detecting a deadlock that has already occurred is easily possible since the resources that each process has locked and/or currently requested are known to the resource scheduler of the operating system.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] *Resource preemption:* resources allocated to various processes may be successively preempted and allocated to other processes until the deadlock is broken.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] Deadlock prevention works by preventing one of the four Coffman conditions from occurring.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] Similar to deadlock prevention, deadlock avoidance approach ensures that deadlock will not occur in a system.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] The term "deadlock avoidance" appears to be very close to "deadlock prevention" in a linguistic context, but they are very much different in the context of deadlock handling.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] Deadlock avoidance does not impose any conditions as seen in prevention but, here each resource request is carefully analyzed to see whether it could be safely fulfilled without causing deadlock.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] Deadlock avoidance requires that the operating system be given in advance additional information concerning which resources a process will request and use during its lifetime.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] Deadlock avoidance algorithm analyzes each and every request by examining that there is no possibility of deadlock occurrence in the future if the requested resource is allocated.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] The drawback of this approach is its requirement of information in advance about how resources are to be requested in the future.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] One of the most used deadlock avoidance algorithms is Banker's algorithm.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] A *livelock* is similar to a deadlock, except that the states of the processes involved in the livelock constantly change with regard to one another, none progressing.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] Ashcroft in a 1975 paper in connection with an examination of airline booking systems.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] Livelock is a special case of resource starvation; the general definition only states that a specific process is not progressing.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] Livelock is a risk with some algorithms that detect and recover from *deadlock*.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] If more than one process takes action, the deadlock detection algorithm can be repeatedly triggered.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] This can be avoided by ensuring that only one process (chosen arbitrarily or by priority) takes action.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] Unlike in centralized systems, detecting and resolving distributed deadlocks is more complex due to the lack of shared memory and the need for coordination among nodes.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] Techniques like wait-for graphs, distributed algorithms (like edge chasing; e.g., Chandy-Misra-Haas), and deadlock prevention (e.g., timeout-based methods) are used to handle such scenarios.
[src:trio-async/deadlock-computer-science] The challenge lies in ensuring consistency and avoiding false positives/negatives due to network delays or partial failures.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] In computer science, **futures**, **promises**, **delays**, and **deferreds** are constructs used for synchronizing program execution in some concurrent programming languages.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Each is an object that acts as a proxy for a result that is initially unknown, usually because the computation of its value is not yet complete.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The term *promise* was proposed in 1976 by Daniel P.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Friedman and David Wise, and Peter Hibbard called it *eventual*.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] A somewhat similar concept *future* was introduced in 1977 in a paper by Henry Baker and Carl Hewitt.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The terms *future*, *promise*, *delay*, and *deferred* are often used interchangeably, although there can be some differences in usage between *future* and *promise*.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Specifically, when usage is distinguished, a future is a *read-only* placeholder view of a variable, while a promise is a writable, single assignment container which sets the value of the future.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Notably, a future may be defined without specifying which specific promise will set its value, and different possible promises may set the value of a given future, though this can be done only once for a given future.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] In other cases a future and a promise are created together and associated with each other: the future is the value, the promise is the function that sets the value – essentially the return value (future) of an asynchronous function (promise).
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Setting the value of a future is also called *resolving*, *fulfilling*, or *binding* it.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Futures and promises originated in functional programming and related paradigms (such as logic programming) to decouple a value (a future) from how it was computed (a promise), allowing the computation to be done more flexibly, notably by parallelizing it.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Later, it found use in distributed computing, in reducing the latency from communication round trips.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Later still, it gained more use by allowing writing asynchronous programs in direct style, rather than in continuation-passing style.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Use of futures may be *implicit* (any use of the future automatically obtains its value, as if it were an ordinary reference) or *explicit* (the user must call a function to obtain the value, such as the `get` method of `java.util.concurrent.Future`in Java).
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Obtaining the value of an explicit future can be called *stinging* or *forcing*.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Explicit futures can be implemented as a library, whereas implicit futures are usually implemented as part of the language.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The original Baker and Hewitt paper described implicit futures, which are naturally supported in the actor model of computation and pure object-oriented programming languages like Smalltalk.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The Friedman and Wise paper described only explicit futures, probably reflecting the difficulty of efficiently implementing implicit futures on stock hardware.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The difficulty is that stock hardware does not deal with futures for primitive data types like integers.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] For example, an add instruction does not know how to deal with `3 + *future* factorial(100000)`.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] In pure actor or object languages this problem can be solved by sending `*future* factorial(100000)` the message `+[3]`, which asks the future to add `3` to itself and return the result.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Note that the message passing approach works regardless of when `factorial(100000)` finishes computation and that no stinging/forcing is needed.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The use of futures can dramatically reduce latency in distributed systems.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] For instance, futures enable *promise pipelining*, as implemented in the languages E and Joule, which was also called *call-stream* in the language Argus.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Each statement needs a message to be sent and a reply received before the next statement can proceed.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Suppose, for example, that `x`, `y`, `t1`, and `t2` are all located on the same remote machine.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] In this case, two complete network round-trips to that machine must take place before the third statement can begin to execute.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The third statement will then cause yet another round-trip to the same remote machine.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The syntax used here is that of the language E, where `x <- a()` means to send the message `a()` asynchronously to `x`.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] All three variables are immediately assigned futures for their results, and execution proceeds to subsequent statements.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Later attempts to resolve the value of `t3` may cause a delay; however, pipelining can reduce the number of round-trips needed.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] If, as in the prior example, `x`, `y`, `t1`, and `t2` are all located on the same remote machine, a pipelined implementation can compute `t3` with one round-trip instead of three.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Because all three messages are destined for objects which are on the same remote machine, only one request need be sent and only one response need be received containing the result.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The send `t1 <- c(t2)` would not block even if `t1` and `t2` were on different machines to each other, or to `x` or `y`.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Promise pipelining should be distinguished from parallel asynchronous message passing.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The relative latency advantage of pipelining becomes even greater in more complicated situations involving many messages.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Promise pipelining also should not be confused with pipelined message processing in actor systems, where it is possible for an actor to specify and begin executing a behaviour for the next message before having completed processing of the current message.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Support for read-only views is consistent with the principle of least privilege, since it enables the ability to set the value to be restricted to subjects that need to set it.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] In a system that also supports pipelining, the sender of an asynchronous message (with result) receives the read-only promise for the result, and the target of the message receives the resolver.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Some languages, such as Alice ML, define futures that are associated with a specific thread that computes the future's value.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] This computation can start either eagerly when the future is created, or lazily when its value is first needed.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] A lazy future is similar to a thunk, in the sense of a delayed computation.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Alice ML also supports futures that can be resolved by any thread, and calls these *promises*.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] This use of *promise* is different from its use in E as described above.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] In Alice, a promise is not a read-only view, and promise pipelining is unsupported.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Instead, pipelining naturally happens for futures, including ones associated with promises.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] If the value of a future is accessed asynchronously, for example by sending a message to it, or by explicitly waiting for it using a construct such as `when` in E, then there is no difficulty in delaying until the future is resolved before the message can be received or the wait completes.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] This is the only case to be considered in purely asynchronous systems such as pure actor languages.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] However, in some systems it may also be possible to attempt to *immediately* or *synchronously* access a future's value.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] As an example of the first possibility, in C++11, a thread that needs the value of a future can block until it is available by calling the `wait()` or `get()` member functions.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] A timeout can also be specified on the wait using the `wait_for()` or `wait_until()` member functions to avoid indefinite blocking.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] If the future arose from a call to `std::async` then a blocking wait (without a timeout) may cause synchronous invocation of the function to compute the result on the waiting thread.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] An *I-var* (as in the language Id) is a future with blocking semantics as defined above.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] An *I-structure* is a data structure containing I-vars.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] A related synchronization construct that can be set multiple times with different values is called an *M-var*.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] M-vars support atomic operations to *take* or *put* the current value, where taking the value also sets the M-var back to its initial *empty* state.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] A *concurrent logic variable* is similar to a future, but is updated by unification, in the same way as *logic variables* in logic programming.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Thus it can be bound more than once to unifiable values, but cannot be set back to an empty or unresolved state.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The dataflow variables of Oz act as concurrent logic variables, and also have blocking semantics as mentioned above.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] A *concurrent constraint variable* is a generalization of concurrent logic variables to support constraint logic programming: the constraint may be *narrowed* multiple times, indicating smaller sets of possible values.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Typically there is a way to specify a thunk that should run whenever the constraint is narrowed further; this is needed to support *constraint propagation*.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Eager thread-specific futures can be straightforwardly implemented in non-thread-specific futures, by creating a thread to calculate the value at the same time as creating the future.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] In this case it is desirable to return a read-only view to the client, so that only the newly created thread is able to resolve this future.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] To implement implicit lazy thread-specific futures (as provided by Alice ML, for example) in terms in non-thread-specific futures, needs a mechanism to determine when the future's value is first needed (for example, the `WaitNeeded` construct in Oz).
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] If all values are objects, then the ability to implement transparent forwarding objects is sufficient, since the first message sent to the forwarder indicates that the future's value is needed.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Non-thread-specific futures can be implemented in thread-specific futures, assuming that the system supports message passing, by having the resolving thread send a message to the future's own thread.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] However, this can be viewed as unneeded complexity.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] In programming languages based on threads, the most expressive approach seems to be to provide a mix of non-thread-specific futures, read-only views, and either a *WaitNeeded* construct, or support for transparent forwarding.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The evaluation strategy of futures, which may be termed *call by future*, is non-deterministic: the value of a future will be evaluated at some time between when the future is created and when its value is used, but the precise time is not determined beforehand and can change from run to run.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The computation can start as soon as the future is created (eager evaluation) or only when the value is actually needed (lazy evaluation), and may be suspended part-way through, or executed in one run.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Once the value of a future is assigned, it is not recomputed on future accesses; this is like the memoization used in call by need.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] A **lazy future** is a future that deterministically has lazy evaluation semantics: the computation of the future's value starts when the value is first needed, as in call by need.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Lazy futures are of use in languages which evaluation strategy is by default not lazy.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] For example, in C++11 such lazy futures can be created by passing the `std::launch::deferred` launch policy to `std::async`, along with the function to compute the value.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] If it does not already have a response, then *R* is stored in the queue of requests inside the *F*.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] However, some futures can deal with requests in special ways to provide greater parallelism.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] For example, the expression `1 + future factorial(n)` can create a new future that will behave like the number `1+factorial(n)`.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] suspends until the future for `factorial(n)` has responded to the request asking if `m` is greater than itself.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The *future* and/or *promise* constructs were first implemented in programming languages such as MultiLisp and Act 1.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The use of logic variables for communication in concurrent logic programming languages was quite similar to futures.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] These began in *Prolog with Freeze* and *IC Prolog*, and became a true concurrency primitive with Relational Language, Concurrent Prolog, guarded Horn clauses (GHC), Parlog, Strand, Vulcan, Janus, Oz-Mozart, Flow Java, and Alice ML.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The single-assignment *I-var* from dataflow programming languages, originating in Id and included in Reppy's *Concurrent ML*, is much like the concurrent logic variable.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The promise pipelining technique (using futures to overcome latency) was invented by Barbara Liskov and Liuba Shrira in 1988, and independently by Mark S.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Miller, Dean Tribble and Rob Jellinghaus in the context of Project Xanadu circa 1989.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The term *promise* was coined by Liskov and Shrira, although they referred to the pipelining mechanism by the name *call-stream*, which is now rarely used.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] It seems that promises and call-streams were never implemented in any public release of Argus, the programming language used in the Liskov and Shrira paper.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The Xanadu implementation of promise pipelining only became publicly available with the release of the source code for Udanax Gold in 1999, and was never explained in any published document.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The later implementations in Joule and E support fully first-class promises and resolvers.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Several early actor languages, including the Act series, supported both parallel message passing and pipelined message processing, but not promise pipelining.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] After 2000, a major revival of interest in futures and promises occurred, due to their use in responsiveness of user interfaces, and in web development, due to the request–response model of message-passing.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] This has subsequently been adopted by other languages, notably Dart (2014), Python (2015), Hack (HHVM), and drafts of ECMAScript 7 (JavaScript), Scala, and C++ (2011).
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Some programming languages are supporting futures, promises, concurrent logic variables, dataflow variables, or I-vars, either by direct language support or in the standard library.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Futures can be implemented in coroutines or generators, resulting in the same evaluation strategy (e.g., cooperative multitasking or lazy evaluation).
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] Futures can easily be implemented in channels: a future is a one-element channel, and a promise is a process that sends to the channel, fulfilling the future.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] This allows futures to be implemented in concurrent programming languages with support for channels, such as CSP and Go.
[src:trio-async/futures-and-promises] The resulting futures are explicit, as they must be accessed by reading from the channel, rather than only evaluation.
