[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Almost every other function in Trio requires that you be inside a call to `run()`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] When writing code using Trio, it’s very important to understand the concept of a *checkpoint*.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Many of Trio’s functions act as checkpoints.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] It’s a point where the Trio scheduler checks its scheduling policy to see if it’s a good time to switch to another task, and potentially does so.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] (Currently, this check is very simple: the scheduler always switches at every checkpoint.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] When writing Trio code, you need to keep track of where your checkpoints are.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] First, because checkpoints require extra scrutiny: whenever you execute a checkpoint, you need to be prepared to handle a `Cancelled` error, or for another task to run and rearrange some state out from under you.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] So when you’re doing code review on a project that uses Trio, one of the things you’ll want to think about is whether there are enough checkpoints, and whether each one is handled correctly.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Of course this means you need a way to recognize checkpoints.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] The underlying principle is that any operation that blocks has to be a checkpoint.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This makes sense: if an operation blocks, then it might block for a long time, and you’ll want to be able to cancel it if a timeout expires; and in any case, while this task is blocked we want another task to be scheduled to run so our code can make full use of the CPU.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] But if we want to write correct code in practice, then this principle is a little too sloppy and imprecise to be useful.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] How do we know which functions might block?
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] What if a function blocks sometimes, but not others, depending on the arguments passed / network speed / phase of the moon?
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] How do we figure out where the checkpoints are when we’re stressed and sleep deprived but still want to get this code review right, and would prefer to reserve our mental energy for thinking about the actual logic instead of worrying about checkpoints?
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Since checkpoints are important and ubiquitous, we make it as simple as possible to keep track of them.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] The reason we distinguish between Trio functions and other functions is that we can’t make any guarantees about third party code.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Checkpoint-ness is a transitive property: if function A acts as a checkpoint, and you write a function that calls function A, then your function also acts as a checkpoint.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] that never calls any of Trio’s async functions.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This is an async function, but it’s not a checkpoint.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] But why make a function async if it never calls any async functions?
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] If you have a function that’s not calling any async functions, then you should make it synchronous.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] The people who use your function will thank you, because it makes it obvious that your function is not a checkpoint, and their code reviews will go faster.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] (Remember how in the tutorial we emphasized the importance of the “async sandwich”, and the way it means that `await` ends up being a marker that shows when you’re calling a function that calls a function that … eventually calls one of Trio’s built-in async functions?
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] The transitivity of async-ness is a technical requirement that Python imposes, but since it exactly matches the transitivity of checkpoint-ness, we’re able to exploit it to help you keep track of checkpoints.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Here the function acts as a checkpoint if you call it with `should_sleep` set to a true value, but not otherwise.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This is why we emphasize that Trio’s own async functions are *unconditional* checkpoints: they *always* check for cancellation and check for scheduling, regardless of what arguments they’re passed.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] If you find an async function in Trio that doesn’t follow this rule, then it’s a bug and you should let us know.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Inside Trio, we’re very picky about this, because Trio is the foundation of the whole system so we think it’s worth the extra effort to make things extra predictable.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] It’s up to you how picky you want to be in your code.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] If called with an `nbytes` that’s greater than zero, then it will call `sock.recv` at least once, and `recv` is an async Trio function, and thus an unconditional checkpoint.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] So in this case, `recv_exactly` acts as a checkpoint.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] But if we do `await recv_exactly(sock, 0)`, then it will immediately return an empty buffer without executing a checkpoint.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] If this were a function in Trio itself, then this wouldn’t be acceptable, but you may decide you don’t want to worry about this kind of minor edge case in your own code.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] The vast majority of Trio’s API is *not* thread safe: it can only be used from inside a call to `trio.run()`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This manual doesn’t bother documenting this on individual calls; unless specifically noted otherwise, you should assume that it isn’t safe to call any Trio functions from anywhere except the Trio thread.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Every call to `run()` has an associated clock.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] By default, Trio uses an unspecified monotonic clock, but this can be changed by passing a custom clock object to `run()` (e.g. for testing).
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] You should not assume that Trio’s internal clock matches any other clock you have access to, including the clocks of simultaneous calls to `trio.run()` happening in other processes or threads!
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] The default clock is currently implemented as `time.perf_counter()` plus a large random offset.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Returns the current time according to Trio’s internal clock.
