[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Trio has a rich, composable system for cancelling work, either explicitly or when a timeout expires.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] We refer to `move_on_after()` as creating a “cancel scope”, which contains all the code that runs inside the `with` block.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] If the HTTP request takes more than 30 seconds to run, then it will be cancelled: we’ll abort the request and we *won’t* see `result is ...` printed on the console; instead we’ll go straight to printing the `with block finished` message.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Note that this is a single 30 second timeout for the entire body of the `with` statement.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This is different from what you might have seen with other Python libraries, where timeouts often refer to something more complicated.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] We think this way is easier to reason about.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] There’s no magic here: Trio is built using ordinary Python functionality, so we can’t just abandon the code inside the `with` block.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Instead, we take advantage of Python’s standard way of aborting a large and complex piece of code: we raise an exception.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Here’s the idea: whenever you call a cancellable function like `await trio.sleep(...)` or `await sock.recv(...)` – see Checkpoints – then the first thing that function does is to check if there’s a surrounding cancel scope whose timeout has expired, or otherwise been cancelled.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] If so, then instead of performing the requested operation, the function fails immediately with a `Cancelled` exception.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] In this example, this probably happens somewhere deep inside the bowels of `do_http_get`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] The exception then propagates out like any normal exception (you could even catch it if you wanted, but that’s generally a bad idea), until it reaches the `with move_on_after(...):`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] And at this point, the `Cancelled` exception has done its job – it’s successfully unwound the whole cancelled scope – so `move_on_after()` catches it, and execution continues as normal after the `with` block.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] And this all works correctly even if you have nested cancel scopes, because every `Cancelled` object carries an invisible marker that makes sure that the cancel scope that triggered it is the only one that will catch it.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Pretty much any code you write using Trio needs to have some strategy to handle `Cancelled` exceptions – even if you didn’t set a timeout, then your caller might (and probably will).
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] You can catch `Cancelled`, but you shouldn’t!
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Or more precisely, if you do catch it, then you should do some cleanup and then re-raise it or otherwise let it continue propagating (unless you encounter an error, in which case it’s OK to let that propagate instead).
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] To help remind you of this fact, `Cancelled` inherits from `BaseException`, like `KeyboardInterrupt` and `SystemExit` do, so that it won’t be caught by catch-all `except Exception:` blocks.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] It’s also important in any long-running code to make sure that you regularly check for cancellation, because otherwise timeouts won’t work!
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This happens implicitly every time you call a cancellable operation; see below for details.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] If you have a task that has to do a lot of work without any I/O, then you can use `await sleep(0)` to insert an explicit cancel+schedule point.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Here’s a rule of thumb for designing good Trio-style (“trionic”?) APIs: if you’re writing a reusable function, then you shouldn’t take a `timeout=` parameter, and instead let your caller worry about it.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] First, it leaves the caller’s options open for deciding how they prefer to handle timeouts – for example, they might find it easier to work with absolute deadlines instead of relative timeouts.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] If they’re the ones calling into the cancellation machinery, then they get to pick, and you don’t have to worry about it.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Second, and more importantly, this makes it easier for others to reuse your code.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Of course, this rule doesn’t apply to APIs that need to impose internal timeouts.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] For example, if you write a `start_http_server` function, then you probably should give your caller some way to configure timeouts on individual requests.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] You can freely nest cancellation blocks, and each `Cancelled` exception “knows” which block it belongs to.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] So long as you don’t stop it, the exception will keep propagating until it reaches the block that raised it, at which point it will stop automatically.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] In this code, the outer scope will expire after 5 seconds, causing the `sleep()` call to return early with a `Cancelled` exception.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Then this exception will propagate through the `with move_on_after(10)` line until it’s caught by the `with move_on_after(5)` context manager.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] The end result is that Trio has successfully cancelled exactly the work that was happening within the scope that was cancelled.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Looking at this, you might wonder how you can tell whether the inner block timed out – perhaps you want to do something different, like try a fallback procedure or report a failure to our caller.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] The `cancel_scope` object also allows you to check or adjust this scope’s deadline, explicitly trigger a cancellation without waiting for the deadline, check if the scope has already been cancelled, and so forth – see `CancelScope` below for the full details.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Cancellations in Trio are “level triggered”, meaning that once a block has been cancelled, *all* cancellable operations in that block will keep raising `Cancelled`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This helps avoid some pitfalls around resource clean-up.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Now suppose that the remote server stops responding, so our call to `await conn.send_hello_msg()` hangs forever.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Fortunately, we were clever enough to put a timeout around this code, so eventually the timeout will expire and `send_hello_msg` will raise `Cancelled`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] But then, in the `finally` block, we make another blocking operation, which will also hang forever!
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] At this point, if we were using `asyncio` or another library with “edge-triggered” cancellation, we’d be in trouble: since our timeout already fired, it wouldn’t fire again, and at this point our application would lock up forever.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] But in Trio, this *doesn’t* happen: the `await conn.send_goodbye_msg()` call is still inside the cancelled block, so it will also raise `Cancelled`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Of course, if you really want to make another blocking call in your cleanup handler, Trio will let you; it’s trying to prevent you from accidentally shooting yourself in the foot.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Intentional foot-shooting is no problem (or at least – it’s not Trio’s problem).
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] So long as you’re inside a scope with `shield = True` set, then you’ll be protected from outside cancellations.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Note though that this *only* applies to *outside* cancellations: if `CLEANUP_TIMEOUT` expires then `await conn.send_goodbye_msg()` will still be cancelled, and if `await conn.send_goodbye_msg()` call uses any timeouts internally, then those will continue to work normally as well.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This is a pretty advanced feature that most people probably won’t use, but it’s there for the rare cases where you need it.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] We’ve talked a lot about what happens when an operation is cancelled, and how you need to be prepared for this whenever calling a cancellable operation… but we haven’t gone into the details about which operations are cancellable, and how exactly they behave when they’re cancelled.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Here’s the rule: if it’s in the `trio` namespace, and you use `await` to call it, then it’s cancellable (see Checkpoints above).
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] There are a few idiosyncratic cases where external constraints make it impossible to fully implement these semantics.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] For example, closing a TLS-wrapped socket normally involves sending a notification to the remote peer, so that they can be cryptographically assured that you really meant to close the socket, and your connection wasn’t just broken by a man-in-the-middle attacker.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] But handling this robustly is a bit tricky.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Remember our example above where the blocking `send_goodbye_msg` caused problems?
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] That’s exactly how closing a TLS socket works: if the remote peer has disappeared, then our code may never be able to actually send our shutdown notification, and it would be nice if it didn’t block forever trying.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Therefore, the method for closing a TLS-wrapped socket will *try* to send that notification – and if it gets cancelled, then it will give up on sending the message, but *will* still close the underlying socket before raising `Cancelled`, so at least you don’t leak that resource.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] `move_on_after()` and all the other cancellation facilities provided by Trio are ultimately implemented in terms of `CancelScope` objects.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] A *cancellation scope*: the link between a unit of cancellable work and Trio’s cancellation system.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Inside the `with` block, a cancellation of `cancel_scope` (via a call to its `cancel()` method or via the expiry of its `deadline`) will immediately interrupt the `long_running_operation()` by raising `Cancelled` at its next checkpoint.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] The context manager `__enter__` returns the `CancelScope` object itself, so you can also write `with trio.CancelScope() as cancel_scope:`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] If a cancel scope becomes cancelled before entering its `with` block, the `Cancelled` exception will be raised at the first checkpoint inside the `with` block.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This allows a `CancelScope` to be created in one task and passed to another, so that the first task can later cancel some work inside the second.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Cancel scopes are not reusable or reentrant; that is, each cancel scope can be used for at most one `with` block.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] The `CancelScope` constructor takes initial values for the cancel scope’s `deadline` and `shield` attributes; these may be freely modified after construction, whether or not the scope has been entered yet, and changes take immediate effect.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] An absolute time on the current run’s clock at which this scope will automatically become cancelled.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Note that for efficiency, the core run loop only checks for expired deadlines every once in a while.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This means that in certain cases there may be a short delay between when the clock says the deadline should have expired, and when checkpoints start raising `Cancelled`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This is a very obscure corner case that you’re unlikely to notice, but we document it for completeness.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Defaults to `math.inf`, which means “no deadline”, though this can be overridden by the `deadline=` argument to the `CancelScope` constructor.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] The number of seconds remaining until this scope’s deadline, relative to the current time.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] When modified Before entering: sets the deadline relative to when the scope enters.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] After entering: sets a new deadline relative to the current time.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] So long as this is set to `True`, then the code inside this scope will not receive `Cancelled` exceptions from scopes that are outside this scope.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] They can still receive `Cancelled` exceptions from (1) this scope, or (2) scopes inside this scope.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Defaults to `False`, though this can be overridden by the `shield=` argument to the `CancelScope` constructor.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Returns False if both deadline and relative_deadline are inf.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] The optional `reason` argument accepts a string, which will be attached to any resulting `Cancelled` exception to help you understand where that cancellation is coming from and why it happened.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This method is idempotent, i.e., if the scope was already cancelled then this method silently does nothing.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Records whether this scope caught a `Cancelled` exception.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This requires two things: (1) the `with` block exited with a `Cancelled` exception, and (2) this scope is the one that was responsible for triggering this `Cancelled` exception.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Records whether cancellation has been requested for this scope, either by an explicit call to `cancel()` or by the deadline expiring.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This attribute being True does *not* necessarily mean that the code within the scope has been, or will be, affected by the cancellation.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] For example, if `cancel()` was called after the last checkpoint in the `with` block, when it’s too late to deliver a `Cancelled` exception, then this attribute will still be True.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This attribute is mostly useful for debugging and introspection.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] If you want to know whether or not a chunk of code was actually cancelled, then `cancelled_caught` is usually more appropriate.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Often there is no need to create `CancelScope` object.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Trio already includes `cancel_scope` attribute in a task-related `Nursery` object.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] We will cover nurseries later in the manual.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Use as a context manager to create a cancel scope whose deadline is set to now + *seconds*.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] The deadline of the cancel scope is calculated upon entering.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Use as a context manager to create a cancel scope with the given absolute deadline.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Creates a cancel scope with the given timeout, and raises an error if it is actually cancelled.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This function and `move_on_after()` are similar in that both create a cancel scope with a given timeout, and if the timeout expires then both will cause `Cancelled` to be raised within the scope.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] The difference is that when the `Cancelled` exception reaches `move_on_after()`, it’s caught and discarded.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] When it reaches `fail_after()`, then it’s caught and `TooSlowError` is raised in its place.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Creates a cancel scope with the given deadline, and raises an error if it is actually cancelled.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This function and `move_on_at()` are similar in that both create a cancel scope with a given absolute deadline, and if the deadline expires then both will cause `Cancelled` to be raised within the scope.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] The difference is that when the `Cancelled` exception reaches `move_on_at()`, it’s caught and discarded.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] When it reaches `fail_at()`, then it’s caught and `TooSlowError` is raised in its place.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Returns the current effective deadline for the current task.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] This function examines all the cancellation scopes that are currently in effect (taking into account shielding), and returns the deadline that will expire first.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] One example of where this might be is useful is if your code is trying to decide whether to begin an expensive operation like an RPC call, but wants to skip it if it knows that it can’t possibly complete in the available time.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] Another example would be if you’re using a protocol like gRPC that propagates timeout information to the remote peer; this function gives a way to fetch that information so you can send it along.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] If this is called in a context where a cancellation is currently active (i.e., a blocking call will immediately raise `Cancelled`), then returned deadline is `-inf`.
