[src:trio-async/reference-core-p01] the effective deadline, as an absolute time.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] One of Trio’s core design principles is: *no implicit concurrency*.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Every function executes in a straightforward, top-to-bottom manner, finishing each operation before moving on to the next – *like Guido intended*.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] But, of course, the entire point of an async library is to let you do multiple things at once.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] The one and only way to do that in Trio is through the task spawning interface.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] So if you want your program to walk *and* chew gum, this is the section for you.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Most libraries for concurrent programming let you start new child tasks (or threads, or whatever) willy-nilly, whenever and where-ever you feel like it.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Trio is a bit different: you can’t start a child task unless you’re prepared to be a responsible parent.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] This means that tasks form a tree: when you call `run()`, then this creates an initial task, and all your other tasks will be children, grandchildren, etc. of the initial task.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Essentially, the body of the `async with` block acts like an initial task that’s running inside the nursery, and then each call to `nursery.start_soon` adds another task that runs in parallel.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Since all tasks are descendents of the initial task, one consequence of this is that `run()` can’t finish until all tasks have finished.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] This code will wait 5 seconds (for the child task to finish), and then return.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] In Trio, child tasks inherit the parent nursery’s cancel scopes.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Note that what matters here is the scopes that were active when `open_nursery()` was called, *not* the scopes active when `start_soon` is called.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Well, `start_soon()` returns as soon as it has scheduled the new task to start running.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] The flow of execution in the parent then continues on to exit the `with trio.move_on_after(TIMEOUT):` block, at which point Trio forgets about the timeout entirely.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] In order for the timeout to apply to the child task, Trio must be able to tell that its associated cancel scope will stay open for at least as long as the child task is executing.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] And Trio can only know that for sure if the cancel scope block is outside the nursery block.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] You might wonder why Trio can’t just remember “this task should be cancelled in `TIMEOUT` seconds”, even after the `with trio.move_on_after(TIMEOUT):` block is gone.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] The reason has to do with how cancellation is implemented.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Recall that cancellation is represented by a `Cancelled` exception, which eventually needs to be caught by the cancel scope that caused it.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] If you want a timeout to apply to one task but not another, then you need to put the cancel scope in that individual task’s function – `child()`, in this example.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Normally, in Python, only one thing happens at a time, which means that only one thing can go wrong at a time.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Obviously `parent` should raise some error, but what?
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] The answer is that both exceptions are grouped in an `ExceptionGroup`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] `ExceptionGroup` and its parent class `BaseExceptionGroup` are used to encapsulate multiple exceptions being raised at once.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] To catch individual exceptions encapsulated in an exception group, the `except*` clause was introduced in Python 3.11 (**PEP 654**).
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] If you want to reraise exceptions, or raise new ones, you can do so, but be aware that exceptions raised in `except*` sections will be raised together in a new exception group.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] But what if you can’t use Python 3.11, and therefore `except*`, just yet?
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] The semantics for the handler functions are equal to `except*` blocks, except for setting local variables.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Structured concurrency is still a relatively new design pattern, but there are a few approaches we’ve identified for how you (or your users) might want to handle groups of exceptions.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Note that the final pattern, simply raising an `ExceptionGroup`, is the most common - and nurseries automatically do that for you.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] This pattern can often be implemented using a decorator or a context manager, such as `trio_util.multi_error_defer_to()` or `trio_util.defer_to_cancelled()`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Note however that re-raising a ‘leaf’ exception will discard whatever part of the traceback is attached to the `ExceptionGroup` itself, so we don’t recommend this for errors that will be presented to humans.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] The simple option here is to `raise MySpecificError from group`, allowing users to handle your library-specific error.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] This is simple and reliable, but doesn’t completely hide the nursery.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] *Do not* unwrap single exceptions if there could ever be multiple exceptions though; that always ends in latent bugs and then tears.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] The more complex option is to ensure that only one exception can in fact happen at a time.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] This is *very hard*, for example you’ll need to handle `KeyboardInterrupt` somehow, and we strongly recommend having a `raise PleaseReportBug from group` fallback just in case you get a group containing more than one exception.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] This is useful when writing a context manager which starts some background tasks, and then yields to user code which effectively runs ‘inline’ in the body of the nursery block.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] In this case, the background tasks can be wrapped with e.g. the outcome library to ensure that only one exception can be raised (from end-user code); and then you can either `raise SomeInternalError` if a background task failed, or unwrap the user exception if that was the only error.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] In early versions of Trio, the `except*` syntax hadn’t be dreamt up yet, and we hadn’t worked with structured concurrency for long or in large codebases.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] As a concession to convenience, some APIs would therefore raise single exceptions, and only wrap concurrent exceptions in the old `trio.MultiError` type if there were two or more.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Unfortunately, the results were not good: calling code often didn’t realize that some function *could* raise a `MultiError`, and therefore handle only the common case - with the result that things would work well in testing, and then crash under heavier load (typically in production).
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] `asyncio.TaskGroup` learned from this experience and *always* wraps errors into an `ExceptionGroup`, as does `anyio`, and as of Trio 0.25 that’s our default behavior too.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] We currently support a compatibility argument `strict_exception_groups=False` to `trio.run` and `trio.open_nursery`, which restores the old behavior (although `MultiError` itself has been fully removed).
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] We strongly advise against it for new code, and encourage existing uses to migrate - we consider the option deprecated and plan to remove it after a period of documented and then runtime warnings.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Sometimes it doesn’t make sense for the task that starts a child to take on responsibility for watching it.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] For example, a server task may want to start a new task for each connection, but it can’t listen for connections and supervise children at the same time.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] The solution here is simple once you see it: there’s no requirement that a nursery object stay in the task that created it!
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Notice that `server` opens a nursery and passes it to `new_connection_listener`, and then `new_connection_listener` is able to start new tasks as “siblings” of itself.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] ...but sometimes things aren’t so simple, and this trick comes in handy.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] One thing to remember, though: cancel scopes are inherited from the nursery, **not** from the task that calls `start_soon`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] The default cleanup logic is often sufficient for simple cases, but what if you want a more sophisticated supervisor?
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] For example, maybe you have Erlang envy and want features like automatic restart of crashed tasks.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Trio itself doesn’t provide these kinds of features, but you can build them on top; Trio’s goal is to enforce basic hygiene and then get out of your way.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] This works by starting a set of tasks which each try to run their function.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] As soon as the first function completes its execution, the task will set the nonlocal variable `winner` from the outer scope to the result of the function, and cancel the other tasks using the passed in cancel scope.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Once all tasks have been cancelled (which exits the nursery block), the variable `winner` will be returned.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Here if one or more of the racing functions raises an unhandled exception then Trio’s normal handling kicks in: it cancels the others and then propagates the exception.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] If you want different behavior, you can get that by adding a `try` block to the `jockey` function to catch exceptions and handle them however you like.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Suppose you’re writing a server that responds to network requests, and you log some information about each request as you process it.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] In this log, it’s hard to know which lines came from which request.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] This way we can see that request 1 was slow: it started before request 2 but finished afterwards.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Now, here’s the problem: how does the logging code know what the request identifier is?
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Sometimes this is the right solution, but other times it would be much more convenient if we could store the identifier in a global variable, so that the logging function could look it up whenever it needed it.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] Except… a global variable can only have one value at a time, so if we have multiple handlers running at once then this isn’t going to work.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] What we need is something that’s *like* a global variable, but that can have different values depending on which request handler is accessing it.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] To solve this problem, Python has a module in the standard library: `contextvars`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p02] For more information, read the contextvars docs.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Trio provides a standard set of synchronization and inter-task communication primitives.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] These objects’ APIs are generally modelled off of the analogous classes in the standard library, but with some differences.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] The standard library synchronization primitives have a variety of mechanisms for specifying timeouts and blocking behavior, and of signaling whether an operation returned due to success versus a timeout.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] These classes are all guaranteed to be “fair”, meaning that when it comes time to choose who will be next to acquire a lock, get an item from a queue, etc., then it always goes to the task which has been waiting longest.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] It’s not entirely clear whether this is the best choice, but for now that’s how it works.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] As an example of what this means, here’s a small program in which two tasks compete for a lock.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Notice that the task which releases the lock always immediately attempts to re-acquire it, before the other task has a chance to run.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] A waitable boolean value useful for inter-task synchronization, inspired by `threading.Event`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] An event object has an internal boolean flag, representing whether the event has happened yet.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] The flag is initially False, and the `wait()` method waits until the flag is True.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If the flag is already True, then `wait()` returns immediately.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] (If the event has already happened, there’s nothing to wait for.) The `set()` method sets the flag to True, and wakes up any waiters.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] This behavior is useful because it helps avoid race conditions and lost wakeups: it doesn’t matter whether `set()` gets called just before or after `wait()`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If you want a lower-level wakeup primitive that doesn’t have this protection, consider `Condition` or `trio.lowlevel.ParkingLot`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Unlike `threading.Event`, `trio.Event` has no `clear` method.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] In Trio, once an `Event` has happened, it cannot un-happen.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If you need to represent a series of events, consider creating a new `Event` object for each one (they’re cheap!), or other synchronization methods like channels or `trio.lowlevel.ParkingLot`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Return the current value of the internal flag.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Set the internal flag value to True, and wake any waiting tasks.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Return an object containing debugging information.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Block until the internal flag value becomes True.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If it’s already True, then this method returns immediately.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] An object containing debugging information.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] The core channel API is defined by the abstract base classes `trio.abc.SendChannel` and `trio.abc.ReceiveChannel`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] You can use these to implement your own custom channels, that do things like pass objects between processes or over the network.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Open a channel for passing objects between tasks within a process.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Memory channels are lightweight, cheap to allocate, and entirely in-memory.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] They don’t involve any operating-system resources, or any kind of serialization.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] They just pass Python objects directly between tasks (with a possible stop in an internal buffer along the way).
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Channel objects can be closed by calling `aclose` or using `async with`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] They are *not* automatically closed when garbage collected.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Closing memory channels isn’t mandatory, but it is generally a good idea, because it helps avoid situations where tasks get stuck waiting on a channel when there’s no-one on the other side.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] See Clean shutdown with channels for details.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Memory channel operations are all atomic with respect to cancellation, either `receive` will successfully return an object, or it will raise `Cancelled` while leaving the channel unchanged.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] A pair `(send_channel, receive_channel)`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If you have trouble remembering which order these go in, remember: data flows from left → right.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If you’ve used the `threading` or `asyncio` modules, you may be familiar with `queue.Queue` or `asyncio.Queue`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] In Trio, `open_memory_channel()` is what you use when you’re looking for a queue.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] The main difference is that Trio splits the classic queue interface up into two objects.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] The advantage of this is that it makes it possible to put the two ends in different processes without rewriting your code, and that we can close the two sides separately.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Close this send channel object asynchronously.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] This returns a new `MemorySendChannel` object, which acts as a duplicate of the original: sending on the new object does exactly the same thing as sending on the old object.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] However, closing one of the objects does not close the other, and receivers don’t get `EndOfChannel` until *all* clones have been closed.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] This is useful for communication patterns that involve multiple producers all sending objects to the same destination.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If you give each producer its own clone of the `MemorySendChannel`, and then make sure to close each `MemorySendChannel` when it’s finished, receivers will automatically get notified when all producers are finished.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] See Managing multiple producers and/or multiple consumers for examples.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Close this send channel object synchronously.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] All channel objects have an asynchronous `aclose` method.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Memory channels can also be closed synchronously.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] This has the same effect on the channel and other tasks using it, but `close` is not a trio checkpoint.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] This simplifies cleaning up in cancelled tasks.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Using `with send_channel:` will close the channel object on leaving the with block.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Memory channels allow multiple tasks to call `send` at the same time.
