[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Returns a `MemoryChannelStatistics` for the memory channel this is associated with.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Close this receive channel object asynchronously.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] This returns a new `MemoryReceiveChannel` object, which acts as a duplicate of the original: receiving on the new object does exactly the same thing as receiving on the old object.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] However, closing one of the objects does not close the other, and the underlying channel is not closed until all clones are closed.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] This is useful for communication patterns that involve multiple consumers all receiving objects from the same underlying channel.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] The clones all share the same underlying channel.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Whenever a clone `receive()`s a value, it is removed from the channel and the other clones do *not* receive that value.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If you want to send multiple copies of the same stream of values to multiple destinations, like `itertools.tee()`, then you need to find some other solution; this method does *not* do that.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Close this receive channel object synchronously.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Using `with receive_channel:` will close the channel object on leaving the with block.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Memory channels allow multiple tasks to call `receive` at the same time.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] The first task will get the first item sent, the second task will get the second item sent, and so on.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Like `receive`, but if there’s nothing ready to receive, raises `WouldBlock` instead of blocking.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Of course we don’t generally like it when programs hang.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] The problem is that the producer sent 3 messages and then exited, but the consumer has no way to tell that the producer is gone: for all it knows, another message might be coming along any moment.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] So it hangs forever waiting for the 4th message.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Here’s a new version that fixes this: it produces the same output as the previous version, and then exits cleanly.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] The really important thing here is the producer’s `async with` .
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] When the producer exits, this closes the `send_channel`, and that tells the consumer that no more messages are coming, so it can cleanly exit its `async for` loop.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Then the program shuts down because both tasks have exited.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] We also added an `async with` to the consumer.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] This isn’t as important, but it can help us catch mistakes or other problems.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] For example, suppose that the consumer exited early for some reason – maybe because of a bug.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Then the producer would be sending messages into the void, and might get stuck indefinitely.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] But, if the consumer closes its `receive_channel`, then the producer will get a `BrokenResourceError` to alert it that it should stop sending messages because no-one is listening.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If you want to see the effect of the consumer exiting early, try adding a `break` statement to the `async for` loop – you should see a `BrokenResourceError` from the producer.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] You can also have multiple producers, and multiple consumers, all sharing the same channel.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] However, this makes shutdown a little more complicated.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] The two producers, A and B, send 3 messages apiece.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] These are then randomly distributed between the two consumers, X and Y.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] However, on most runs, that’s not what happens – the first part of the output is OK, and then when we get to the end the program crashes with `ClosedResourceError`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If you run the program a few times, you’ll see that sometimes the traceback shows `send` crashing, and other times it shows `receive` crashing, and you might even find that on some runs it doesn’t crash at all.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Here’s what’s happening: suppose that producer A finishes first.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] It exits, and its `async with` block closes the `send_channel`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Producer B was still using that `send_channel`… so the next time B calls `send`, it gets a `ClosedResourceError`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Sometimes, though if we’re lucky, the two producers might finish at the same time (or close enough), so they both make their last `send` before either of them closes the `send_channel`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] But, even if that happens, we’re not out of the woods yet!
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] After the producers exit, the two consumers race to be the first to notice that the `send_channel` has closed.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] It exits its `async for` loop, then exits the `async with` block… and closes the `receive_channel`, while Y is still using it.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] We could avoid this by using some complicated bookkeeping to make sure that only the *last* producer and the *last* consumer close their channel endpoints… but that would be tiresome and fragile.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] This example demonstrates using the `MemorySendChannel.clone` and `MemoryReceiveChannel.clone` methods.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] What these do is create copies of our endpoints, that act just like the original – except that they can be closed independently.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] And the underlying channel is only closed after *all* the clones have been closed.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] So this completely solves our problem with shutdown, and if you run this program, you’ll see it print its six lines of output and then exits cleanly.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Notice a small trick we use: the code in `main` creates clone objects to pass into all the child tasks, and then closes the original objects using `async with`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] But this is more error-prone, especially if you use a loop to spawn the producers/consumers.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Here we pass clones into the tasks, but never close the original objects.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] That means we have 3 send channel objects (the original + two clones), but we only close 2 of them, so the consumers will hang around forever waiting for that last one to be closed.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] When you call `open_memory_channel()`, you have to specify how many values can be buffered internally in the channel.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If the buffer is full, then any task that calls `send()` will stop and wait for another task to call `receive()`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] This is useful because it produces *backpressure*: if the channel producers are running faster than the consumers, then it forces the producers to slow down.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] You can disable buffering entirely, by doing `open_memory_channel(0)`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] In that case any task that calls `send()` will wait until another task calls `receive()`, and vice versa.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] This is similar to how channels work in the classic Communicating Sequential Processes model, and is a reasonable default if you aren’t sure what size buffer to use.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] At the other extreme, you can make the buffer unbounded by using `open_memory_channel(math.inf)`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] In this case, `send()` *always* returns immediately.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] On average, the producer sends ten messages per second, but the consumer only calls `receive` once per second.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] That means that each second, the channel’s internal buffer has to grow to hold an extra nine items.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] After a minute, the buffer will have ~540 items in it; after an hour, that grows to ~32,400.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Eventually, the program will run out of memory.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] And well before we run out of memory, our latency on handling individual messages will become abysmal.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] For example, at the one minute mark, the producer is sending message ~600, but the consumer is still processing message ~60.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Message 600 will have to sit in the channel for ~9 minutes before the consumer catches up and processes it.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Now try replacing `open_memory_channel(math.inf)` with `open_memory_channel(0)`, and run it again.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Now the `send` calls wait for the `receive` calls to finish, which forces the producer to slow down to match the consumer’s speed.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Now, let’s try setting a small but nonzero buffer size, like `open_memory_channel(3)`. what do you think will happen?
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] So you can see that the producer runs ahead by 3 messages, and then stops to wait: when the consumer reads message 1, it sends message 4, then when the consumer reads message 2, it sends message 5, and so on.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Once it reaches the steady state, this version acts just like our previous version where we set the buffer size to 0, except that it uses a bit more memory and each message sits in the buffer for a bit longer before being processed (i.e., the message latency is higher).
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Of course real producers and consumers are usually more complicated than this, and in some situations, a modest amount of buffering might improve throughput.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] But too much buffering wastes memory and increases latency, so if you want to tune your application you should experiment to see what value works best for you.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Personally, I find that events and channels are usually enough to implement most things I care about, and lead to easier to read code than the lower-level primitives discussed in this section.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] (If you find yourself reaching for these because you’re trying to implement a new higher-level synchronization primitive, then you might also want to check out the facilities in `trio.lowlevel` for a more direct exposure of Trio’s underlying synchronization logic.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] An object for controlling access to a resource with limited capacity.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Sometimes you need to put a limit on how many tasks can do something at the same time.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] For example, you might want to use some threads to run multiple blocking I/O operations in parallel… but if you use too many threads at once, then your system can become overloaded and it’ll actually make things slower.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] One popular solution is to impose a policy like “run up to 40 threads at the same time, but no more”.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] But how do you implement a policy like this?
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] And crucially, if you try to borrow a token but the sack is empty, then you have to wait for another task to finish what it’s doing and put its token back first before you can take it and continue.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Another way to think of it: a `CapacityLimiter` is like a sofa with a fixed number of seats, and if they’re all taken then you have to wait for someone to get up before you can sit down.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] By default, `trio.to_thread.run_sync()` uses a `CapacityLimiter` to limit the number of threads running at once; see `trio.to_thread.current_default_thread_limiter` for details.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If you’re familiar with semaphores, then you can think of this as a restricted semaphore that’s specialized for one common use case, with additional error checking.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] For a more traditional semaphore, see `Semaphore`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Don’t confuse this with the “leaky bucket” or “token bucket” algorithms used to limit bandwidth usage on networks.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] The basic idea of using tokens to track a resource limit is similar, but this is a very simple sack where tokens aren’t automatically created or destroyed over time; they’re just borrowed and then put back.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Borrow a token from the sack, blocking if necessary.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Borrow a token from the sack, without blocking.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Borrow a token from the sack on behalf of `borrower`, blocking if necessary.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Borrow a token from the sack on behalf of `borrower`, without blocking.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] The amount of capacity that’s available to use.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] The amount of capacity that’s currently in use.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Put a token back into the sack on behalf of `borrower`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] You can change `total_tokens` by assigning to this attribute.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If you make it larger, then the appropriate number of waiting tasks will be woken immediately to take the new tokens.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If you decrease total_tokens below the number of tasks that are currently using the resource, then all current tasks will be allowed to finish as normal, but no new tasks will be allowed in until the total number of tasks drops below the new total_tokens.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] A semaphore holds an integer value, which can be incremented by calling `release()` and decremented by calling `acquire()` – but the value is never allowed to drop below zero.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If the value is zero, then `acquire()` will block until someone calls `release()`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If you’re looking for a `Semaphore` to limit the number of tasks that can access some resource simultaneously, then consider using a `CapacityLimiter` instead.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] This object’s interface is similar to, but different from, that of `threading.Semaphore`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] A `Semaphore` object can be used as an async context manager; it blocks on entry but not on exit.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Decrement the semaphore value, blocking if necessary to avoid letting it drop below zero.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Attempt to decrement the semaphore value, without blocking.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Increment the semaphore value, possibly waking a task blocked in `acquire()`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] This is a non-reentrant, single-owner lock.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Unlike `threading.Lock`, only the owner of the lock is allowed to release it.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] A `Lock` object can be used as an async context manager; it blocks on entry but not on exit.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Acquire the lock, blocking if necessary.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Attempt to acquire the lock, without blocking.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Check whether the lock is currently held.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] True if the lock is held, False otherwise.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] A variant of `Lock` where tasks are guaranteed to acquire the lock in strict first-come-first-served order.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] (For example, when using h2 simply reading incoming data can occasionally create outgoing data to send.) The challenge is to make sure that these chunks are sent in the correct order, without being garbled.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If you’re using h2 then *usually* reading incoming data doesn’t create the need to send any data, so we don’t want to force every task that tries to read from the network to sit and wait a potentially long time for `sendall` to finish.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] And in some situations this could even potentially cause a deadlock, if the remote peer is waiting for you to read some data before it accepts the data you’re sending.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] `StrictFIFOLock` provides an alternative.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] First we do all our interaction with the state machine in a single scheduling quantum (notice there are no `await`s in there), so it’s automatically atomic with respect to other tasks.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] And then if and only if we have data to send, we get in line to send it – and `StrictFIFOLock` guarantees that each task will send its data in the same order that the state machine generated it.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Currently, `StrictFIFOLock` is identical to `Lock`, but (a) this may not always be true in the future, especially if Trio ever implements more sophisticated scheduling policies, and (b) the above code is relying on a pretty subtle property of its lock.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Using a `StrictFIFOLock` acts as an executable reminder that you’re relying on this property.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] A classic condition variable, similar to `threading.Condition`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] A `Condition` object can be used as an async context manager to acquire the underlying lock; it blocks on entry but not on exit.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Acquire the underlying lock, blocking if necessary.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Attempt to acquire the underlying lock, without blocking.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Check whether the underlying lock is currently held.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Wake one or more tasks that are blocked in `wait()`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Wake all tasks that are currently blocked in `wait()`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] Wait for another task to call `notify()` or `notify_all()`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] When calling this method, you must hold the lock.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] It releases the lock while waiting, and then re-acquires it before waking up.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] There is a subtlety with how this method interacts with cancellation: when cancelled it will block to re-acquire the lock before raising `Cancelled`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] This may cause cancellation to be less prompt than expected.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] If we didn’t re-acquire the lock before waking up, and `wait()` were cancelled here, then we’d crash in `condition.__aexit__` when we tried to release the lock we no longer held.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] These primitives return statistics objects that can be inspected.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] An object containing debugging information for a Lock.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p03] An object containing debugging information for a Condition.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Python 3.6 added support for *async generators*, which can use `await`, `async for`, and `async with` in between their `yield` statements.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] As you might expect, you use `async for` to iterate over them.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] **PEP 525** has many more details if you want them.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Trio supports async generators, but there’s several caveats and it’s very hard to handle them properly.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Therefore Trio bundles a helper, `trio.as_safe_channel` that does it for you.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Decorate an async generator function to make it cancellation-safe.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] The `yield` keyword offers a very convenient way to write iterators… which makes it really unfortunate that async generators are so difficult to call correctly.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Yielding from the inside of a cancel scope or a nursery to the outside violates structured concurrency with consequences explained in **PEP 789**.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Even then, resource cleanup errors remain common (**PEP 533**) unless you wrap every call in `aclosing()`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] This decorator gives you the best of both worlds: with careful exception handling and a background task we preserve structured concurrency by offering only the safe interface, and you can still write your iterables with the convenience of `yield`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] While the combined async-with-async-for can be inconvenient at first, the context manager is indispensable for both correctness and for prompt cleanup of resources.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] The details behind the problems are described in the following sections.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] If you iterate over an async generator in its entirety, like the example above does, then the execution of the async generator will occur completely in the context of the code that’s iterating over it, and there aren’t too many surprises.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] If you abandon a partially-completed async generator, though, such as by `break`ing out of the iteration, things aren’t so simple.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] The async generator iterator object is still alive, waiting for you to resume iterating it so it can produce more values.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] At some point, Python will realize that you’ve dropped all references to the iterator, and will call on Trio to throw in a `GeneratorExit` exception so that any remaining cleanup code inside the generator has a chance to run: `finally` blocks, `__aexit__` handlers, and so on.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Unfortunately, Python provides no guarantees about *when* this happens.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] It could be as soon as you break out of the `async for` loop, or an arbitrary amount of time later.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] It could even be after the entire Trio run has finished!
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Just about the only guarantee is that it *won’t* happen in the task that was using the generator.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] That task will continue on with whatever else it’s doing, and the async generator cleanup will happen “sometime later, somewhere else”: potentially with different context variables, not subject to timeouts, and/or after any nurseries you’re using have been closed.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] This is cumbersome, but Python unfortunately doesn’t provide any other reliable options.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] If you use `aclosing()`, then your generator’s cleanup code executes in the same context as the rest of its iterations, so timeouts, exceptions, and context variables work like you’d expect.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] If you plan to run your code on PyPy to take advantage of its better performance, you should be aware that PyPy is *far more likely* than CPython to perform async generator cleanup at a time well after the last use of the generator.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] You may not write a `yield` statement that suspends an async generator inside a `CancelScope` or `Nursery` that was entered within the generator.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Async generators decorated with `@asynccontextmanager` to serve as the template for an async context manager are *not* subject to this constraint, because `@asynccontextmanager` uses them in a limited way that doesn’t create problems.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Violating the rule described in this section will sometimes get you a useful error message, but Trio is not able to detect all such cases, so sometimes you’ll get an unhelpful `TrioInternalError`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] (And sometimes it will seem to work, which is probably the worst outcome of all, since then you might not notice the issue until you perform some minor refactoring of the generator or the code that’s iterating it, or just get unlucky.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] The reason for the restriction on cancel scopes has to do with the difficulty of noticing when a generator gets suspended and resumed.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] The cancel scopes inside the generator shouldn’t affect code running outside the generator, but Trio isn’t involved in the process of exiting and reentering the generator, so it would be hard pressed to keep its cancellation plumbing in the correct state.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Nurseries use a cancel scope internally, so they have all the problems of cancel scopes plus a number of problems of their own: for example, when the generator is suspended, what should the background tasks do?
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] There’s no good way to suspend them, but if they keep running and throw an exception, where can that exception be reraised?
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] For more discussion, see Trio issues 264 (especially this comment) and 638.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] In a perfect world, all third-party libraries and low-level APIs would be natively async and integrated into Trio, and all would be happiness and rainbows.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Until it does, you may find yourself needing to interact with non-Trio APIs that do rude things like “blocking”.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] In acknowledgment of this reality, Trio provides two useful utilities for working with real, operating-system level, `threading`-module-style threads.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] First, if you’re in Trio but need to push some blocking I/O into a thread, there’s `trio.to_thread.run_sync`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] And if you’re in a thread and need to communicate back with Trio, you can use `trio.from_thread.run()` and `trio.from_thread.run_sync()`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] If you’ve used other I/O frameworks, you may have encountered the concept of a “thread pool”, which is most commonly implemented as a fixed size collection of threads that hang around waiting for jobs to be assigned to them.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] These solve two different problems: First, reusing the same threads over and over is more efficient than starting and stopping a new thread for every job you need done; basically, the pool acts as a kind of cache for idle threads.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] And second, having a fixed size avoids getting into a situation where 100,000 jobs are submitted simultaneously, and then 100,000 threads are spawned and the system gets overloaded and crashes.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Instead, the N threads start executing the first N jobs, while the other (100,000 - N) jobs sit in a queue and wait their turn.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Which is generally what you want, and this is how `trio.to_thread.run_sync()` works by default.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] The downside of this kind of thread pool is that sometimes, you need more sophisticated logic for controlling how many threads are run at once.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] For example, you might want a policy like “at most 20 threads total, but no more than 3 of those can be running jobs associated with the same user account”, or you might want a pool whose size is dynamically adjusted over time in response to system conditions.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] It’s even possible for a fixed-size policy to cause unexpected deadlocks.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Imagine a situation where we have two different types of blocking jobs that you want to run in the thread pool, type A and type B.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Type A is pretty simple: it just runs and completes pretty quickly.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] But type B is more complicated: it has to stop in the middle and wait for some other work to finish, and that other work includes running a type A job.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Now, suppose you submit N jobs of type B to the pool.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] They all start running, and then eventually end up submitting one or more jobs of type A.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] But since every thread in our pool is already busy, the type A jobs don’t actually start running – they just sit in a queue waiting for the type B jobs to finish.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] But the type B jobs will never finish, because they’re waiting for the type A jobs.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] The ideal solution to this problem is to avoid having type B jobs in the first place – generally it’s better to keep complex synchronization logic in the main Trio thread.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] But if you can’t do that, then you need a custom thread allocation policy that tracks separate limits for different types of jobs, and make it impossible for type B jobs to fill up all the slots that type A jobs need to run.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] So, we can see that it’s important to be able to change the policy controlling the allocation of threads to jobs.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Trio’s solution to this problem is to split worker thread management into two layers.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] The lower layer is responsible for taking blocking I/O jobs and arranging for them to run immediately on some worker thread.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] It takes care of solving the tricky concurrency problems involved in managing threads and is responsible for optimizations like reusing threads, but has no admission control policy: if you give it 100,000 jobs, it will spawn 100,000 threads.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] The upper layer is responsible for providing the policy to make sure that this doesn’t happen – but since it *only* has to worry about policy, it can be much simpler.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] In fact, all there is to it is the `limiter=` argument passed to `trio.to_thread.run_sync()`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] This defaults to a global `CapacityLimiter` object, which gives us the classic fixed-size thread pool behavior.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] (See `trio.to_thread.current_default_thread_limiter()`.) But if you want to use “separate pools” for type A jobs and type B jobs, then it’s just a matter of creating two separate `CapacityLimiter` objects and passing them in when running these jobs.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Convert a blocking operation into an async operation using a thread.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] except that if `sync_fn` takes a long time, then the first line will block the Trio loop while it runs, while the second line allows other Trio tasks to continue working while `sync_fn` runs.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] This is accomplished by pushing the call to `sync_fn(*args)` off into a worker thread.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] From inside the worker thread, you can get back into Trio using the functions in `trio.from_thread`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] You should not use this function to call long-running CPU-bound functions!
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] If you need to do this, you’re better off using a worker process, or perhaps PyPy (which still has a GIL, but may do a better job of fairly allocating CPU time between threads).
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Get the default `CapacityLimiter` used by `trio.to_thread.run_sync`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] The most common reason to call this would be if you want to modify its `total_tokens` attribute.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Run the given async function in the parent Trio thread, blocking until it is complete.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Returns or raises whatever the given function returns or raises.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Run the given sync function in the parent Trio thread, blocking until it is complete.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] This will probably be clearer with an example.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] The `from_thread.run*` functions reuse the host task that called `trio.to_thread.run_sync()` to run your provided function, as long as you’re using the default `abandon_on_cancel=False` so Trio can be sure that the task will remain around to perform the work.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] If you pass `abandon_on_cancel=True` at the outset, or if you provide a `TrioToken` when calling back in to Trio, your functions will be executed in a new system task.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Therefore, the `current_task()`, `current_effective_deadline()`, or other task-tree specific values may differ depending on keyword argument values.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] You can also use `trio.from_thread.check_cancelled()` to check for cancellation from a thread that was spawned by `trio.to_thread.run_sync()`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] If the call to `run_sync()` was cancelled, then `check_cancelled()` will raise `trio.Cancelled()`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] It’s like `trio.from_thread.run(trio.sleep, 0)`, but much faster.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Raise `trio.Cancelled` if the associated Trio task entered a cancelled status.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] To be precise, `check_cancelled()` checks whether the task running `trio.to_thread.run_sync()` has ever been cancelled since the last time it was running a `trio.from_thread.run()` or `trio.from_thread.run_sync()` function.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] It may raise `trio.Cancelled` even if a cancellation occurred that was later hidden by a modification to `trio.CancelScope.shield` between the cancelled `CancelScope` and `trio.to_thread.run_sync()`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] This differs from the behavior of normal Trio checkpoints, which raise `Cancelled` only if the cancellation is still active when the checkpoint executes.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] The distinction here is *exceedingly* unlikely to be relevant to your application, but we mention it for completeness.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] When working with threads, you can use the same `contextvars` we discussed above, because their values are preserved.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] That means that the values of the context variables are accessible even in worker threads, or when sending a function to be run in the main/parent Trio thread using `trio.from_thread.run` *from* one of these worker threads.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] But it also means that as the context is not the same but a copy, if you `set` the context variable value *inside* one of these functions that work in threads, the new value will only be available in that context (that was copied).
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] So, the new value will be available for that function and other internal/children tasks, but the value won’t be available in the parent thread.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] If you need to modify values that would live in the context variables and you need to make those modifications from the child threads, you can instead set a mutable object (e.g. a dictionary) in the context variable of the top level/parent Trio thread.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Then in the children, instead of setting the context variable, you can `get` the same object, and modify its values.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] That way you keep the same object in the context variable and only mutate it in child threads.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] This way, you can modify the object content in child threads and still access the new content in the parent thread.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] If you are using `contextvars` or you are using a library that uses them, now you know how they interact when working with threads in Trio.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] But have in mind that in many cases it might be a lot simpler to *not* use context variables in your own code and instead pass values in arguments, as it might be more explicit and might be easier to reason about.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] The context is automatically copied instead of using the same parent context because a single context can’t be used in more than one thread, it’s not supported by `contextvars`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] This can make it difficult to iterate quickly since you have to redefine the whole function body whenever you make a tweak.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Trio provides a modified interactive console that lets you `await` at the top level.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] If you are an IPython user, you can use IPython’s autoawait function.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] This can be enabled within the IPython shell by running the magic command `%autoawait trio`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] To have `autoawait` enabled whenever Trio installed, you can add the following to your IPython startup files.
