[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] To remind you of this, it inherits from `BaseException` instead of `Exception`, just like `KeyboardInterrupt` and `SystemExit` do.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] then this *won’t* catch a `Cancelled` exception.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Attempting to do so will produce a `TypeError`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] In the US it’s also common to see this word spelled “canceled”, with only one “l”.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] This is a recent and US-specific innovation, and even in the US both forms are still commonly used.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] So for consistency with the rest of the world and with “cancellation” (which always has two “l”s), Trio uses the two “l” spelling everywhere.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Raised by `fail_after()` and `fail_at()` if the timeout expires.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Raised by `X_nowait` functions if `X` would block.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Raised when trying to receive from a `trio.abc.ReceiveChannel` that has no more data to receive.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] This is analogous to an “end-of-file” condition, but for channels.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Raised when a task attempts to use a resource that some other task is already using, and this would lead to bugs and nonsense.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] For example, if two tasks try to send data through the same socket at the same time, Trio will raise `BusyResourceError` instead of letting the data get scrambled.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Raised when attempting to use a resource after it has been closed.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Note that “closed” here means that *your* code closed the resource, generally by calling a method with a name like `close` or `aclose`, or by exiting a context manager.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] If a problem arises elsewhere – for example, because of a network failure, or because a remote peer closed their end of a connection – then that should be indicated by a different exception class, like `BrokenResourceError` or an `OSError` subclass.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Raised when an attempt to use a resource fails due to external circumstances.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] For example, you might get this if you try to send data on a stream where the remote side has already closed the connection.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] You *don’t* get this error if *you* closed the resource – in that case you get `ClosedResourceError`.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] This exception’s `__cause__` attribute will often contain more information about the underlying error.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Raised by `trio.from_thread.run` and similar functions if the corresponding call to `trio.run()` has already finished.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Raised by `run()` if we encounter a bug in Trio, or (possibly) a misuse of one of the low-level `trio.lowlevel` APIs.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] If you get this error, please file a bug.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Unfortunately, if you get this error it also means that all bets are off – Trio doesn’t know what is going on and its normal invariants may be void.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] (For example, we might have “lost track” of a task.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Or lost track of all tasks.) Again, though, this shouldn’t happen.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Warning emitted if you use deprecated Trio functionality.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] While a relatively mature project, Trio remains committed to refining its design and improving usability.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] As part of this, we occasionally deprecate or remove functionality that proves suboptimal.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] If you use Trio, we recommend subscribing to issue #1 to get information about upcoming deprecations and other backwards compatibility breaking changes.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] Despite the name, this class currently inherits from `FutureWarning`, not `DeprecationWarning`, because until a 1.0 release, we want these warnings to be visible by default.
[src:trio-async/reference-core-p04] You can hide them by installing a filter or with the `-W` switch: see the `warnings` documentation for details.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] In computer science, **synchronization** is the task of coordinating multiple processes to join up or handshake at a certain point, in order to reach an agreement or commit to a certain sequence of action.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] The need for synchronization does not arise merely in multi-processor systems but for any kind of concurrent processes; even in single processor systems.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Thread synchronization is defined as a mechanism which ensures that two or more concurrent processes or threads do not simultaneously execute some particular program segment known as critical section.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Processes' access to critical section is controlled by using synchronization techniques.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] When one thread starts executing the critical section (serialized segment of the program) the other thread should wait until the first thread finishes.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] If proper synchronization techniques are not applied, it may cause a race condition where the values of variables may be unpredictable and vary depending on the timings of context switches of the processes or threads.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] For example, suppose that there are three processes, namely 1, 2, and 3.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] All three of them are concurrently executing, and they need to share a common resource (critical section) as shown in Figure 1.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Synchronization should be used here to avoid any conflicts for accessing this shared resource.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Hence, when Process 1 and 2 both try to access that resource, it should be assigned to only one process at a time.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] If it is assigned to Process 1, the other process (Process 2) needs to wait until Process 1 frees that resource (as shown in Figure 2).
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Another synchronization requirement which needs to be considered is the order in which particular processes or threads should be executed.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] For example, one cannot board a plane before buying a ticket.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Similarly, one cannot check e-mails before validating the appropriate credentials (for example, user name and password).
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] In the same way, an ATM will not provide any service until it receives a correct PIN.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] One of the challenges for exascale algorithm design is to minimize or reduce synchronization.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Synchronization takes more time than computation, especially in distributed computing.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Reducing synchronization drew attention from computer scientists for decades.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Whereas it becomes an increasingly significant problem recently as the gap between the improvement of computing and latency increases.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Experiments have shown that (global) communications due to synchronization on distributed computers takes a dominated share in a sparse iterative solver.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] This problem is receiving increasing attention after the emergence of a new benchmark metric, the High Performance Conjugate Gradient (HPCG), for ranking the top 500 supercomputers.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] These problems are used to test nearly every newly proposed synchronization scheme or primitive.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Many systems provide hardware support for critical section code.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] A single processor or uniprocessor system could disable interrupts by executing currently running code without preemption, which is very inefficient on multiprocessor systems.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] "The key ability we require to implement synchronization in a multiprocessor is a set of hardware primitives with the ability to atomically read and modify a memory location.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Without such a capability, the cost of building basic synchronization primitives will be too high and will increase as the processor count increases.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] There are a number of alternative formulations of the basic hardware primitives, all of which provide the ability to atomically read and modify a location, together with some way to tell if the read and write were performed atomically.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] These hardware primitives are the basic building blocks that are used to build a wide variety of user-level synchronization operations, including things such as locks and barriers.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] In Java, one way to prevent thread interference and memory consistency errors, is by prefixing a method signature with the *synchronized* keyword, in which case the lock of the declaring object is used to enforce synchronization.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] A second way is to wrap a block of code in a *synchronized(someObject){...}* section, which offers finer-grain control.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] This forces any thread to acquire the lock of *someObject* before it can execute the contained block.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] The lock is automatically released when the thread which acquired the lock leaves this block or enters a waiting state within the block.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Any variable updates made by a thread in a synchronized block become visible to other threads when they similarly acquire the lock and execute the block.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] For either implementation, any object may be used to provide a lock because all Java objects have an *intrinsic lock* or *monitor lock* associated with them when instantiated.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Java *synchronized* blocks, in addition to enabling mutual exclusion and memory consistency, enable signaling—i.e. sending events from threads which have acquired the lock and are executing the code block to those which are waiting for the lock within the block.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Java *synchronized* sections, therefore, combine the functionality of both mutexes and events to ensure synchronization.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Such a construct is known as a synchronization monitor.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] The .NET Framework also uses synchronization primitives.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] "Synchronization is designed to be cooperative, demanding that every thread follow the synchronization mechanism before accessing protected resources for consistent results.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Many programming languages support synchronization and entire specialized languages have been written for embedded application development where strictly deterministic synchronization is paramount.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Another effective way of implementing synchronization is by using spinlocks.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Before accessing any shared resource or piece of code, every processor checks a flag.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] If the flag is reset, then the processor sets the flag and continues executing the thread.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] But, if the flag is set (locked), the threads would keep spinning in a loop and keep checking if the flag is set or not.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Spinlocks are effective only if the flag is reset for lower cycles; otherwise, it can lead to performance issues as it wastes many processor cycles waiting.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Barriers are simple to implement and provide good responsiveness.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] They are based on the concept of implementing wait cycles to provide synchronization.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Consider three threads running simultaneously, starting from barrier 1.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] After time t, thread1 reaches barrier 2 but it still has to wait for thread 2 and 3 to reach barrier2 as it does not have the correct data.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Once all the threads reach barrier 2 they all start again.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] After time t, thread 1 reaches barrier3 but it will have to wait for threads 2 and 3 and the correct data again.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Thus, in barrier synchronization of multiple threads there will always be a few threads that will end up waiting for other threads as in the above example thread 1 keeps waiting for thread 2 and 3.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] This results in severe degradation of the process performance.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Where Wbarrier is the wait time for a thread, Tbarrier is the number of threads has arrived, and Rthread is the arrival rate of threads.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Experiments show that 34% of the total execution time is spent in waiting for other slower threads.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Semaphores are signalling mechanisms which can allow one or more threads/processors to access a section.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] A Semaphore has a flag which has a certain fixed value associated with it and each time a thread wishes to access the section, it decrements the flag.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Similarly, when the thread leaves the section, the flag is incremented.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] If the flag is zero, the thread cannot access the section and gets blocked if it chooses to wait.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Some semaphores would allow only one thread or process in the code section.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Such Semaphores are called binary semaphore and are very similar to Mutex.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Here, if the value of semaphore is 1, the thread is allowed to access and if the value is 0, the access is denied.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Synchronization was originally a process-based concept whereby a lock could be obtained on an object.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] There are two types of (file) lock; read-only and read–write.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Read-only locks may be obtained by many processes or threads.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Readers–writer locks are exclusive, as they may only be used by a single process/thread at a time.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Although locks were derived for file databases, data is also shared in memory between processes and threads.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Sometimes more than one object (or file) is locked at a time.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] If they are not locked simultaneously they can overlap, causing a deadlock exception.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Java and Ada only have exclusive locks because they are thread based and rely on the compare-and-swap processor instruction.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] An abstract mathematical foundation for synchronization primitives is given by the history monoid.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] There are also many higher-level theoretical devices, such as process calculi and Petri nets, which can be built on top of the history monoid.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Following are some synchronization examples with respect to different platforms.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Enabling and disabling of kernel preemption replaced spinlocks on uniprocessor systems.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Prior to kernel version 2.6, Linux disabled interrupt to implement short critical sections.
[src:trio-async/synchronization-computer-science] Since version 2.6 and later, Linux is fully preemptive.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Trio is a modern Python library for writing asynchronous applications – that is, programs that want to do multiple things at the same time with parallelized I/O, like a web spider that fetches lots of pages in parallel, a web server juggling lots of simultaneous downloads… that sort of thing.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Here we’ll try to give a gentle introduction to asynchronous programming with Trio.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] We assume that you’re familiar with Python in general, but don’t worry – we don’t assume you know anything about asynchronous programming or Python’s new `async/await` feature.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Also, unlike many `async/await` tutorials, we assume that your goal is to *use* Trio to write interesting programs, so we won’t go into the nitty-gritty details of how `async/await` is implemented inside the Python interpreter.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] The word “coroutine” is never mentioned.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] The fact is, you really don’t *need* to know any of that stuff unless you want to *implement* a library like Trio, so we leave it out (though we’ll throw in a few links for those who want to dig deeper).
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] We have a friendly chat channel, you can ask questions using the “python-trio” tag on StackOverflow, or just file a bug (if our documentation is confusing, that’s our fault, and we want to fix it!).
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Python 3.5 added a major new feature: async functions.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Using Trio is all about writing async functions, so let’s start there.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] “Async” is short for “asynchronous”; we’ll sometimes refer to regular functions like `regular_double` as “synchronous functions”, to distinguish them from async functions.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] You can’t use the `await` keyword inside the body of a regular function.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] If you try it, you’ll get a syntax error: def print_double(x): print(await async_double(x)) # <-- SyntaxError here But inside an async function, `await` is allowed: async def print_double(x): print(await async_double(x)) # <-- OK!
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] So in summary: As a user, the entire advantage of async functions over regular functions is that async functions have a superpower: they can call other async functions.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] This immediately raises two questions: how, and why?
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] When your Python program starts up, it’s running regular old sync code.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] So there’s a chicken-and-the-egg problem: once we’re running an async function we can call other async functions, but *how* do we call that first async function?
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] And, if the only reason to write an async function is that it can call other async functions, *why* on earth would we ever use them in the first place?
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] I mean, as superpowers go this seems a bit pointless.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Wouldn’t it be simpler to just… not use any async functions at all?
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] This is where an async library like Trio comes in.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] A bunch of useful async functions – in particular, functions for doing I/O.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] So that answers the “why”: these functions are async, and they’re useful, so if you want to use them, you have to write async code.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] If you think keeping track of these `async` and `await` things is annoying, then too bad – you’ve got no choice in the matter!
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] But it turns out that the `async/await` stuff is actually a good thing, for reasons we’ll discuss a little bit later.) Here’s an example function that uses `trio.sleep()`.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] So it turns out our `async_double` function is actually a bad example.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] I mean, it works, it’s fine, there’s nothing *wrong* with it, but it’s pointless: it could just as easily be written as a regular function, and it would be more useful that way.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] `double_sleep` is a much more typical example: we have to make it async, because it calls another async function.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] It’s exactly the functions on the path between `trio.run()` and `trio.whatever` that have to be async.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Trio provides the async bread, and then your code makes up the async sandwich’s tasty async filling.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Other functions (e.g., helpers you call along the way) should generally be regular, non-async functions.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Now would be a good time to open up a Python prompt and experiment a little with writing simple async functions and running them with `trio.run`.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] You might think that Python would raise an error here, like it does for other kinds of mistakes we sometimes make when calling a function.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Like, if we forgot to pass `trio.sleep()` its required argument, then we would get a nice `TypeError` saying so.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] But unfortunately, if you forget an `await`, you don’t get that.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] This is clearly broken – 0.00 seconds is not long enough to feel well rested!
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Yet the code acts like it succeeded – no exception was raised.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] The only clue that something went wrong is that it prints `RuntimeWarning: coroutine 'sleep' was never awaited`.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Also, the exact place where the warning is printed might vary, because it depends on the whims of the garbage collector.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Forgetting an `await` like this is an *incredibly common mistake*.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] And Python will not help you as much as you’d hope 😞.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] I’m not even sure what all that other junk in the PyPy output is.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Fortunately I don’t need to know, I just need to fix my function!
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] (“I thought you said you weren’t going to mention coroutines!” Yes, well, *I* didn’t mention coroutines, Python did.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] In Trio, every time we use `await` it’s to call an async function, and every time we call an async function we use `await`.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] But Python’s trying to keep its options open for other libraries that are *ahem* a little less organized about things.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] and then that object gets passed to `await`, which actually runs the function.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] If you didn’t already mess this up naturally, then give it a try on purpose: try writing some code with a missing `await`, or an extra `await`, and see what you get.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] This way you’ll be prepared for when it happens to you for real.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] And remember: watch out for `RuntimeWarning: coroutine '...' was never awaited`; it means you need to find and fix your missing `await`.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] So now we’ve started using Trio, but so far all we’ve learned to do is write functions that print things and sleep for various lengths of time.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Interesting enough, but we could just as easily have done that with `time.sleep()`.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Trio has one more trick up its sleeve, that makes async functions more powerful than regular functions: it can run multiple async functions *at the same time*.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] There’s a lot going on in here, so we’ll take it one step at a time.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] In the first part, we define two async functions `child1` and `child2`.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] It does this by using a mysterious `async with` statement to create a “nursery”, and then “spawns” `child1` and `child2` into the nursery.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Let’s start with this `async with` thing.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] In regular Python, a statement like `with someobj: ...` instructs the interpreter to call `someobj.__enter__()` at the beginning of the block, and to call `someobj.__exit__()` at the end of the block.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] An `async with` does exactly the same thing, except that where a regular `with` statement calls regular methods, an `async with` statement calls async methods: at the start of the block it does `await someobj.__aenter__()` and at that end of the block it does `await someobj.__aexit__()`.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] In this case we call `someobj` an “async context manager”.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] So in short: `with` blocks are a shorthand for calling some functions, and since with async/await Python now has two kinds of functions, it also needs two kinds of `with` blocks.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] If you understand async functions, then you understand `async with`.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] This example doesn’t use them, but while we’re here we might as well mention the one other piece of new syntax that async/await added: `async for`.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] It’s basically the same idea as `async with` versus `with`: An `async for` loop is just like a `for` loop, except that where a `for` loop does `iterator.__next__()` to fetch the next item, an `async for` does `await async_iterator.__anext__()`.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Basically just remember that it involves making sandwiches and sticking the word “async” in front of everything, and you’ll do fine.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] There are only 4 lines of code that really do anything here.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] On line 20, we use `trio.open_nursery()` to get a “nursery” object, and then inside the `async with` block we call `nursery.start_soon` twice, on lines 22 and 25.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] There are actually two ways to call an async function: the first one is the one we already saw, using `await async_fn()`; the new one is `nursery.start_soon(async_fn)`: it asks Trio to start running this async function, *but then returns immediately without waiting for the function to finish*.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] So after our two calls to `nursery.start_soon`, `child1` and `child2` are now running in the background.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] And then at line 28, the commented line, we hit the end of the `async with` block, and the nursery’s `__aexit__` function runs.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] What this does is force `parent` to stop here and wait for all the children in the nursery to exit.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] This is why you have to use `async with` to get a nursery: it gives us a way to make sure that the child calls can’t run away and get lost.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] One reason this is important is that if there’s a bug or other problem in one of the children, and it raises an exception, then it lets us propagate that exception into the parent; in many other frameworks, exceptions like this are just discarded.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Notice that `child1` and `child2` both start together and then both exit together.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] And, even though we made two calls to `trio.sleep(1)`, the program finished in just one second total.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] So it looks like `child1` and `child2` really are running at the same time!
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Now, if you’re familiar with programming using threads, this might look familiar – and that’s intentional.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] But it’s important to realize that *there are no threads here*.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] All of this is happening in a single thread.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] To remind ourselves of this, we use slightly different terminology: instead of spawning two “threads”, we say that we spawned two “tasks”.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] In the next section, we’ll dig into what this means.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] If all you want to do is use Trio, then you don’t need to understand all the nitty-gritty detail of how this switching works – but it’s very useful to have at least a general intuition about what Trio is doing “under the hood” when your code is executing.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] To help build that intuition, let’s look more closely at how Trio ran our example from the last section.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Fortunately, Trio provides a rich set of tools for inspecting and debugging your programs.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Here we want to watch `trio.run()` at work, which we can do by writing a class we’ll call `Tracer`, which implements Trio’s `Instrument` interface.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] This generates a *lot* of output, so we’ll go through it one step at a time.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] First, there’s a bit of chatter while Trio gets ready to run our code.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Once the initial housekeeping is done, Trio starts running the `parent` function, and you can see `parent` creating the two child tasks.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Each task runs until it hits the call to `trio.sleep()`, and then suddenly we’re back in `trio.run()` deciding what to run next.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] The secret is that `trio.run()` and `trio.sleep()` work together to make it happen: `trio.sleep()` has access to some special magic that lets it pause itself, so it sends a note to `trio.run()` requesting to be woken again after 1 second, and then suspends the task.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] And once the task is suspended, Python gives control back to `trio.run()`, which decides what to do next.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] You might wonder whether you can mix-and-match primitives from different async libraries.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] For example, could we use `trio.run()` together with `asyncio.sleep()`?
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] The answer is no, we can’t, and the paragraph above explains why: the two sides of our async sandwich have a private language they use to talk to each other, and different libraries use different languages.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] So if you try to call `asyncio.sleep()` from inside a `trio.run()`, then Trio will get very confused indeed and probably blow up in some dramatic way.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Only async functions have access to the special magic for suspending a task, so only async functions can cause the program to switch to a different task.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] What this means is that if a call *doesn’t* have an `await` on it, then you know that it *can’t* be a place where your task will be suspended.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] This makes tasks much easier to reason about than threads, because there are far fewer ways that tasks can be interleaved with each other and stomp on each others’ state.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] (For example, in Trio a statement like `a += 1` is always atomic – even if `a` is some arbitrarily complicated custom object!) Trio also makes some further guarantees beyond that, but that’s the big one.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] And now you also know why `parent` had to use an `async with` to open the nursery: if we had used a regular `with` block, then it wouldn’t have been able to pause at the end and wait for the children to finish; we need our cleanup function to be async, which is exactly what `async with` gives us.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] To recap: at this point `parent` is waiting on `child1` and `child2`, and both children are sleeping.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] So `trio.run()` checks its notes, and sees that there’s nothing to be done until those sleeps finish – unless possibly some external I/O event comes in.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] If that happened, then it might give us something to do.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Of course we aren’t doing any I/O here so it won’t happen, but in other situations it could.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] And in fact no I/O does arrive, so one second later we wake up again, and Trio checks its notes again.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] And then the children get to run, and this time they run to completion.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Remember how `parent` is waiting for them to finish?
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Then, after another check for I/O, `parent` wakes up.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] The nursery cleanup code notices that all its children have exited, and lets the nursery block finish.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] That was a lot of text, but again, you don’t need to understand everything here to use Trio – in fact, Trio goes to great lengths to make each task feel like it executes in a simple, linear way.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Alternatively, if this has just whetted your appetite and you want to know more about how `async/await` works internally, then this blog post is a good deep dive, or check out this great walkthrough to see how to build a simple async I/O framework from the ground up.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Speaking of parallelism – let’s zoom out for a moment and talk about how async/await compares to other ways of handling concurrency in Python.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] As we’ve already noted, Trio tasks are conceptually rather similar to Python’s built-in threads, as provided by the `threading` module.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] And in all common Python implementations, threads have a famous limitation: the Global Interpreter Lock, or “GIL” for short.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] The GIL means that even if you use multiple threads, your code still (mostly) ends up running on a single core.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] But from Trio’s point of view, the problem with the GIL isn’t that it restricts parallelism.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] No, the problem with the GIL is that it’s a *lousy deal*: we give up on using multiple cores, and in exchange we get… almost all the same challenges and mind-bending bugs that come with real parallel programming, and – to add insult to injury – pretty poor scalability.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Threads in Python just aren’t that appealing.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Trio doesn’t make your code run on multiple cores; in fact, as we saw above, it’s baked into Trio’s design that when it has multiple tasks, they take turns, so at each moment only one of them is actively running.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] We’re not so much overcoming the GIL as embracing it.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Certainly it’s not appropriate for every app… but there are a lot of situations where the trade-offs here look pretty appealing.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] There is one downside that’s important to keep in mind, though.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Making checkpoints explicit gives you more control over how your tasks can be interleaved – but with great power comes great responsibility.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] With threads, the runtime environment is responsible for making sure that each thread gets its fair share of running time.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] With Trio, if some task runs off and does stuff for seconds on end without executing a checkpoint, then… all your other tasks will just have to wait.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Here’s an example of how this can go wrong.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] Take our example from above, and replace the calls to `trio.sleep()` with calls to `time.sleep()`.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p01] One of the major reasons why Trio has such a rich instrumentation API is to make it possible to write debugging tools to catch issues like this.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Now let’s take what we’ve learned and use it to do some I/O, which is where async/await really shines.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] The traditional toy application for demonstrating network APIs is an “echo server”: a program that awaits arbitrary data from remote clients, and then sends that same data right back.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] In this tutorial, we present both ends of the pipe: the client, and the server.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] The client periodically sends data to the server, and displays its answers.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] The server awaits connections; when a client connects, it recopies the received data back on the pipe.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Note that this code will not work without a TCP server such as the one we’ll implement below.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] The overall structure here should be familiar, because it’s just like our last example: we have a parent task, which spawns two child tasks to do the actual work, and then at the end of the `async with` block it switches into full-time parenting mode while waiting for them to finish.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] But now instead of just calling `trio.sleep()`, the children use some of Trio’s networking APIs.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] First we call `trio.open_tcp_stream()` to make a TCP connection to the server.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] `127.0.0.1` is a magic IP address meaning “the computer I’m running on”, so this connects us to whatever program on the local computer is using `PORT` as its contact point.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] This function returns an object implementing Trio’s `Stream` interface, which gives us methods to send and receive bytes, and to close the connection when we’re done.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] We use an `async with` block to make sure that we do close the connection – not a big deal in a toy example like this, but it’s a good habit to get into, and Trio is designed to make `with` and `async with` blocks easy to use.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Finally, we start up two child tasks, and pass each of them a reference to the stream.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] It uses a loop that alternates between calling `await client_stream.send_all(...)` to send some data (this is the method you use for sending data on any kind of Trio stream), and then sleeping for a second to avoid making the output scroll by too fast on your terminal.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] It uses an `async for` loop to fetch data from the server.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Alternatively, it could use `receive_some`, which is the opposite of `send_all`, but using `async for` saves some boilerplate.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] And now we’re ready to look at the server.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] What this does is call `serve_tcp()`, which is a convenience function Trio provides that runs forever (or at least until you hit control-C or otherwise cancel it).
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] This part works pretty much the same for any server, whether it’s an echo server, HTTP server, SSH server, or whatever, so it makes sense to bundle it all up together in a helper function like this.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Now let’s look at `echo_server`, which handles each client connection – so if there are multiple clients, there might be multiple calls to `echo_server` running at the same time.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] This is where we implement our server’s “echo” behavior.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] The argument `server_stream` is provided by `serve_tcp()`, and is the other end of the connection we made in the client: so the data that the client passes to `send_all` will come out here.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Then we have a `try` block discussed below, and finally the server loop which alternates between reading some data from the socket and then sending it back out again (unless the socket was closed, in which case we quit).
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Remember that in Trio, like Python in general, exceptions keep propagating until they’re caught.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Here we think it’s plausible there might be unexpected exceptions, and we want to isolate that to making just this one task crash, without taking down the whole program.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] On the other hand, if the exception is something like a `KeyboardInterrupt`, we *do* want that to propagate out into the parent task and cause the whole program to exit.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] To express this, we use a `try` block with an `except Exception:` handler.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] In general, Trio leaves it up to you to decide whether and how you want to handle exceptions, just like Python in general.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Open a few terminals, run `echo-server.py` in one, run `echo-client.py` in another, and watch the messages scroll by!
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] When you get bored, you can exit by hitting control-C.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Here’s a question you might be wondering about: why does our client use two separate tasks for sending and receiving, instead of a single task that alternates between them – like the server has?
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] It turns out there are two problems with this – one minor and one major.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] The minor problem is that when we call `receive_some` here we’re not waiting for *all* the data to be available; `receive_some` returns as soon as *any* data is available.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] If `data` is small, then our operating systems / network / server will *probably* keep it all together in a single chunk, but there’s no guarantee.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] If the server sends `hello` then we might get `hello`, or `he` `llo`, or `h` `e` `l` `l` `o`, or … bottom line, any time we’re expecting more than one byte of data, we have to be prepared to call `receive_some` multiple times.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] And where this would go especially wrong is if we find ourselves in the situation where `data` is big enough that it passes some internal threshold, and the operating system or network decide to always break it up into multiple pieces.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Now on each pass through the loop, we send `len(data)` bytes, but read less than that.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] The result is something like a memory leak: we’ll end up with more and more data backed up in the network, until eventually something breaks.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] If you’re curious *how* things break, then you can use `receive_some`'s optional argument to put a limit on how many bytes you read each time, and see what happens.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] This is a bit cumbersome, but it would solve this problem.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] There’s another problem, though, that’s deeper.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] We’re still alternating between sending and receiving.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Notice that when we send data, we use `await`: this means that sending can potentially *block*.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Any data that we send goes first into an operating system buffer, and from there onto the network, and then another operating system buffer on the receiving computer, before the receiving program finally calls `receive_some` to take the data out of these buffers.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] If we call `send_all` with a small amount of data, then it goes into these buffers and `send_all` returns immediately.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] But if we send enough data fast enough, eventually the buffers fill up, and `send_all` will block until the remote side calls `receive_some` and frees up some space.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Now let’s think about this from the server’s point of view.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Each time it calls `receive_some`, it gets some data that it needs to send back.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] And until it sends it back, the data that is sitting around takes up memory.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Computers have finite amounts of RAM, so if our server is well behaved then at some point it needs to stop calling `receive_some` until it gets rid of some of the old data by doing its own call to `send_all`.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] So for the server, really the only viable option is to alternate between receiving and sending.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] But we need to remember that it’s not just the client’s call to `send_all` that might block: the server’s call to `send_all` can also get into a situation where it blocks until the client calls `receive_some`.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] So if the server is waiting for `send_all` to finish before it calls `receive_some`, and our client also waits for `send_all` to finish before it calls `receive_some`,… we have a problem!
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] The client won’t call `receive_some` until the server has called `receive_some`, and the server won’t call `receive_some` until the client has called `receive_some`.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] If our client is written to alternate between sending and receiving, and the chunk of data it’s trying to send is large enough (e.g.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] 10 megabytes will probably do it in most configurations), then the two processes will deadlock.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Moral: Trio gives you powerful tools to manage sequential and concurrent execution.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] In this example we saw that the server needs `send` and `receive_some` to alternate in sequence, while the client needs them to run concurrently, and both were straightforward to implement.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] But when you’re implementing network code like this then it’s important to think carefully about flow control and buffering, because it’s up to you to choose the right execution mode!
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] Other popular async libraries like Twisted and `asyncio` tend to paper over these kinds of issues by throwing in unbounded buffers everywhere.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] This can avoid deadlocks, but can introduce its own problems and in particular can make it difficult to keep memory usage and latency under control.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] While both approaches have their advantages, Trio takes the position that it’s better to expose the underlying problem as directly as possible and provide good tools to confront it head-on.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] If you want to try and make the deadlock happen on purpose to see for yourself, and you’re using Windows, then you might need to split the `send_all` call up into two calls that each send half of the data.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] This is because Windows has a somewhat unusual way of handling buffering.
[src:trio-async/tutorial-p02] TODO: maybe a brief discussion of `KeyboardInterrupt` handling?
